<1ST_LINE>u a AM-People-Piscopo     08-27 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Piscopo,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Value Of Fame Can Be Divided in Divorce, Judge Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has decided comedian Joe
Piscopo's ``celebrity good will'' can be counted as an asset in
dividing property with his wife in a divorce settlement.
   ``It is a quantifiable asset, just as in any other profession,''
Superior Court Judge Isabel B. Stark said Wednesday. But she added
that the way celebrity status should be quantified is ``somewhat
different'' from a partnership or corporation.
   One of Piscopo's attorneys, Gary N. Skoloff, said Thursday it
was only the second time a judge in a divorce case had placed a
value on celebrity status. A judge in New York last March made a
similar ruling regarding actress Marisa Berenson, he said.
   Skoloff, who vowed to appeal the ruling, said it was unclear how
to value Piscopo's celebrity from the judge's oral opinion.
   He said he would have to wait for a written opinion, but added
that under his understanding of what the judge had said, Nancy
Piscopo would be eligible to receive roughly $50,000.
   Piscopo is a onetime star of NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' who
has appeared in several movie comedies, including ``Wise Guys,''
and also appears in a series of beer commercials. He and his wife
separated three years ago.
</TEXT>
