<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FuelEconomy     08-27 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Economy,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transportation Department Proposes Raising Fuel Economy Standard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department proposed setting
a higher fuel-economy standard for the nation's automakers but held
out the prospect the new level would remain less than the 27.5
miles per gallon voted by Congress.
   Under a proposed rule, the corporate average fuel economy
standard would be set between 26.5 mpg and 27.5 mpg for the 1989
and 1990 model years.
   Without the rule, the standard would revert to the 27.5 mpg
voted by Congress in 1975. The standard has been set at 26 mpg
since 1986 under an administrative exception allowed by the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, a branch of the
Transportation Department.
   Two of the Big Three automakers praised the agency's action.
   General Motors Corp. said it would have to limit production of
larger cars should the rule revert to 27.5 mpg. ``This would give
Japanese automakers, who are already planning to import more luxury
and family-size cars with V8 and high-performance V6 engines, a
powerful competitive advantage in the larger car market segments.''
   A 27.5 mpg standard would cause the automaker to reduce
production by 212,000 vehicles at a loss of 76,000 jobs in 1989,
and by 470,000 vehicles, with a loss of 158,000 jobs, in 1990, said
John Hartnett, a GM spokesman.
   A Ford Motor Co. spokesman, Bill Peacock, predicted ``artificial
rationing'' of full-sized cars under a 27.5 mpg standard.
   ``If relief is not granted ... and the standard ticks back up to
27.5, then the vehicles that the industry supplies will not match
the demand level that we're getting from the public,'' he said in
Dearborn, Mich.
   Chrysler Corp., however, said it expects to ``meet the law as it
stands now and will meet it in the coming year,'' said a spokesman,
Tony Cervone.
   ``It is really not a Chrysler issue,'' he said. The company's
cars on average are smaller than those of its larger competitors.
   The 1975 fuel economy law, adopted to reduce petroleum
consumption at a time of rapidly rising prices, requires U.S.
manufacturers to meet an average fuel-consumption level of 27.5 mpg
on all passenger cars they make.
   The law allows the NHTSA to lower the standard below 27.5 mpg if
it finds that manufacturers have made reasonable efforts to achieve
that level.
   Moreover, the law requires the agency to consider whether
achieving the 27.5 mpg level is economically and practically
feasible.
   It was under those provisions of the law that the agency lowered
the standard beginning in 1986.
   Had the agency not proposed new rulemaking on the standard, it
would have automatically reverted to 27.5 mpg in October for the
1989 model year.
   NHTSA scheduled a Sept. 14 public meeting on the proposed rule.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley, in announcing the proposed
rule, called the fuel-economy standard ``a dinosaur that should be
extinct.''
   The standard ``puts domestic manufacturers at a competitive
disadvantage compared to some foreign manufacturers, who have been
building mostly small cars,'' Burnley said. The agency last year
proposed legislation that would abolish the standard.
   The Competitive Enterprise Institute, a free-market advocacy
group which has sued the Transportation Department, alleging the
agency concealed the safety impact of fuel economy standards, said
that even at 26.5 mpg the standard would cause 1,500 to 2,800 more
traffic deaths involving 1989 cars than if there were no standard.
   The additional deaths would occur because the standard would
discourage the manufacturing of larger cars, and crashes of smaller
cars tend to be more deadly, the group said.
</TEXT>
