<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Olson     08-27 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olson,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olson Says He's Glad Probe Has Ended; Will Seek Legal Fee
Reimbursement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Assistant Attorney General Theodore
Olson, informed that an independent counsel will not seek perjury
charges against him, says he is glad the 2{-year probe has ended.
   ``It has been a long and difficult process,'' Olson said Friday
after independent counsel Alexia Morrison notified him that she had
ended her investigation into allegations that Olson perjured
himself in connection with a congressional probe into political
manipulation of the Superfund toxic waste-cleanup program.
   Ms. Morrison, in a statement released by her office, said she
told Olson that ``no indictment will be sought against him.''
   Specifically, Ms. Morrison looked into whether Olson should have
been prosecuted for perjury in connection with testimony he gave
March 10, 1983, before a House Judiciary subcommittee regarding the
withholding of EPA documents.
   Olson, now in private law practice, said he has accumulated
legal bills of between $1 million and $1.5 million for which he
will seek reimbursement from the government. Under the law, people
investigated by independent counsels but not charged are entitled
to collect reasonable fees.
   As required by the 1978 Ethics in Government Act under which
independent counsels are appointed, Ms. Morrison said she will file
her report with a special division of the U.S. Court of Appeals.
That panel will have the authority to release the report, she said.
   Ms. Morrison, who helped begin the investigation of Olson in
April 1986, noted that Olson and two others had challenged the
constitutionality of the independent counsels in the spring of 1987.
   That challenge, which could have affected other independent
counsels such as Lawrence Walsh, the prosecutor in the Iran-Contra
case, was unsuccessful.
   The Supreme Court ruled June 29 that independent counsels were
legal, allowing Ms. Morrison to continue her investigation.
   The case grew out of a congressional investigation into possible
political manipulation of the Superfund, created to pay for
cleanups of toxic waste sites.
   Initially, Washington lawyer James C. McKay was appointed
special counsel on April 24, 1986, by a three-judge panel of the
U.S. Court of Appeals to look into the matter. He resigned the
following month to avoid ``the appearance of a conflict of
interest'' involving his law firm. McKay said another member of his
law firm had given advice to an interested party in the case.
   Ms. Morrison, McKay's deputy, then took over the case.
   The House Judiciary Committee had sought a far broader
investigation than the one that McKay, and later Ms. Morrison, were
told by the judges to conduct.
   The panel wanted a dozen current or former Reagan administration
officials investigated for denying Congress access to hundreds of
documents in 1982 and 1983 that the committee said it needed to
investigate mismanagement by EPA.
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Peter W. Rodino Jr., D-N.J.,
said at the time that then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III, in
seeking an independent counsel with only limited jurisdiction, had
``disregarded overwhelming evidence of other possible wrongdoing''
and appeared ``to have made judgments that are beyond his
authority.''
   But Meese's decision stuck.
   Former EPA Administrator Anne Gorsuch Burford, who resigned at
the height of the controversy, said she urged release of many of
the documents that Congress wanted but that the Justice Department
overruled her.
   The Judiciary Committee said the Justice Department was
generally aware that the files Congress sought contained evidence
of political manipulation of Superfund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
