<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-PLO     08-27 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-PLO,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadline Approaches On PLO Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the deadline approaches, the Reagan
administration is wrestling with a decision on whether to go back
to court to try to close the Palestine Liberation Organization's
office in New York.
   It's a controversial decision, whichever way it goes, and
ultimately President Reagan is likely to have the final word.
   Two months ago, a federal court ruled against Congress and the
Justice Department and said the PLO observer mission at the United
Nations could not be closed under a 1947 U.S. agreement
establishing U.N. headquarters in New York.
   The PLO information office in Washington already has been put
out of business. The New York mission is the only real footing
Yasser Arafat's group has in the United States, which shuns the PLO
as a matter of policy as a promoter of terrorism against Americans
and Israelis.
   The 60 days allowed for an appeal to a higher court regarding
the New York office runs out Monday.
   The issue confronting Reagan, who is vacationing in California,
is whether to authorize an appeal of the decision in order to try
to reverse it _ or to let the deadline pass, which would mean
letting the ruling stand.
   So far, the administration has not made a decision, said Amy
Brown, a Justice Department spokeswoman.
   Reagan apparently is under conflicting pressure. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz opposed the closing of the mission in the
first place, while former Attorney General Edwin Meese III
attempted to enforce Congress' overwhelming decision to shut it
down.
   Meese's successor, Attorney General Richard Thornburgh, is
understood to favor appealing Judge Edmund Palmieri's June 29
decision, while some of Reagan's White House advisers evidently
want to drop the controversial subject by not appealing.
   One of the questions PLO foes are asking is whether Thornburgh's
legal views are reaching the president in California.
   Brown said Thornburgh was in touch with the White House, but she
declined to say whether his opinion had reached Reagan. She also
declined to say where Thornburgh stood on the issue.
   The Justice Department had argued last spring that last year's
anti-terrorism act, which branded the PLO a terrorist organization,
empowered the government to close the observer mission.
   But Judge Palmieri said the government did not have the legal
authority because the law did not supersede the 1947 agreement that
established U.N. headquarters in New York. However, the judge
decided that under the law the government could try to halt PLO
operations apart from the mission itself.
   Palmieri dismissed the government's lawsuit with prejudice _
meaning it cannot be brought again _ although his ruling could be
appealed to a higher court.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, who argued the government's case
before Palmieri, said after the ruling that he and the Justice
Department would study the ruling ``and we will make a decision as
to further proceedings as soon as possible.''
   The head of the PLO mission in New York hailed the decision as a
victory for international law.
   ``The United Nations now has no fear that the host country, or
any host country, can violate its legal obligations and get out
scot-free,'' Zehdi Labib Terzi, permanent observer of the PLO, told
The Associated Press.
   Lawyers for the PLO, including former U.S. Attorney General
Ramsey Clark, had argued that closing the mission would violate
international law because the Headquarters Agreement called for
arbitration of disputes between the United States and the United
Nations.
   They maintained that Palmieri lacked jurisdiction and should
defer to an advisory opinion from the International Court of
Justice, which said the United States was bound to submit to
arbitration.
   But Palmieri rejected those arguments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
