<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     08-27 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Competes with Bush for Attention in Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen is back in his native Texas to give Vice President
George Bush some competition for attention.
   Bentsen extended a planned four-day campaign trip to come here,
where he planned this morning to meet with local law enforcement
people about the Democrats' anti-crime agenda.
   He also told reporters he didn't want Bush's Texas campaign this
week to go without a response. Both Bush and Bentsen claim Texas as
their homes.
   Bentsen was expected to give some tough talk on crime, following
up a couple of days of presenting the national security positions
of the ticket he has joined with Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis.
   Bentsen promised Arkansas Democrats on Friday that he and
Dukakis would ``build up America's military might.'' And he said he
was ``fed up'' with Republicans trying to portray the Democrats as
weak on defense.
   ``We want to build up America's military might, but once again,
it has to be bipartisan cooperation,'' he said.
   Bentsen was cheered repeatedly by the 1,000-strong partisan
crowd, a sharp contrast with a speech Thursday before the Veterans
of Foreign Wars in Chicago, where he was interrupted by boos on
several occasions.
   His message to the Arkansas Democratic Convention in Hot Springs
was that Dukakis was a Democrat they could support _ instead of
voting Republican in the presidential election as they did when
Walter Mondale ran against President Reagan in 1984.
   ``Our message to them in 1988 is: come home to the Democratic
party,'' he said.
   Bentsen's campaign swing was interrupted Friday when his
campaign jet was grounded because of a damaged door. Another plane
was found, but Bentsen missed a campaign stop in Atlanta.
   He planned to return to Washington tonight.
</TEXT>
