<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Angola 2ndLd-Writethru a0794 08-27 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0794,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegates At Angola Talks Fail To Reach Agreement on Cuban Troop
Withdrawal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs with talks ending without agreement. Pick
up 8th graf, `The negotiatiors...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates at the latest round of
southern Africa peace talks ended the two-day session late Friday
without resolving the issue of a timetable for the withdrawal of
Cuba's 50,000 troops from Angola.
   Instead, the delegates agreed to meet again in Brazzaville in
two weeks for more talks.
   The timetable is the key both to ending fighting between
Cuban-backed Angolan forces and South Africa and to independence
for South-West Africa, Angola's southern neighbor that is also
known as Namibia.
   Sources in the South African delegation said substantial
progress was made on Cuban withdrawal. The United States, which
mediated the talks, proposed that the Cubans pull out within 18
months, a compromise the Angolan delegation took home to Luanda
overnight Thursday for consideration by its Marxist government.
   Angola's ambassador to West Germany, Herminio Escorcio, told
reporters upon emerging from the conference: ``It is a question of
flexibility on the part of South Africa and the United States.''
   South Africa has insisted the Cubans be withdrawn within a year
if it is to grant independence to Namibia. Angola has said it would
take three to four years to send the Cubans home.
   The talks among South Africa, Cuba and Angola on ending the
13-year Angolan civil war and granting independence to Namibia
began Wednesday.
   The negotiators also discussed South Africa's support for the
anti-Marxist guerrillas fighting Angola's government, said sources
close to the South African delegation who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Angola was believed to be demanding that South Africa and the
United States stop supporting the rebels in return for concessions
on the timetable.
   The rebels of UNITA _ the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola _ have not been involved in the talks and
have ignored a cease-fire signed by South Africa, Angola and Cuba.
   The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp.,
broadcasting in Johannesburg, said the talks had reached ``a
delicate stage.'' It also said the South African delegation met
with a special United Nations observer present for the Brazzaville
talks.
   The broadcast said the talks concerned the cost of implementing
the U.N. plan for independence for Namibia.
   South Africa has promised to pull its troops out of Angola by
Sept. 1 and grant independence to Namibia within a year as long as
the Cubans withdraw.
   On Thursday, the four parties did not meet, leaving U.S.
mediators to work out a compromise proposal.
   Chester Crocker, secretary of state for African affairs, said
the talks ``were well on their way,'' although it is ``too soon to
anticipate their results.'' He commented in an interview with Congo
radio broadcast Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
