<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq-POWs Bjt   08-27 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq-POWs, Bjt,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Process Ahead For Gulf War Prisoner Exchange</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the Iran-Iraq war apparently nearing
an end, tens of thousands of war prisoners now look ahead to
freedom _ most with joy, but some with dread.
   Iran's deputy foreign minister, Mohammad Larijani, has said a
prisoner exchange could start within three months after the
cease-fire that took effect Aug. 20.
   But Baghdad-based diplomats say repatriation could be delayed by
hard bargaining at Geneva peace talks and by the sheer immensity of
the task of registering all POWs and determining whether they want
to go home.
   ``It's going to be a very long process,'' said one European
diplomat, who like his colleagues, refused to be identified.
   The exact number of POWs is unclear.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross, which has agreed
to organize the exchange, registered 50,182 POWs held by Iran and
19,284 held by Iraq. Red Cross officials say they believe both
sides hold many prisoners who have not been registered.
   Diplomats in Baghdad estimate that Iran holds 60,000-70,000 POWs
and Iraq 30,000-50,000.
   Iran is also believed to hold 10,000 to 20,000 Egyptians
captured while working as mercenaries in the Iraqi army or while
working as fishermen for Kuwait, which Iran accuses of supporting
Iraq.
   Some prisoners have been held since Sept. 1980, when the war
began. But thousands of Iranians were reported captured in Iraqi
offensives in the final days of fighting before the truce began.
   The Iraqis apparently sought to seize as many Iranians as
possible as bargaining chips in the Geneva talks.
   Both sides have used POWs for propaganda purposes, apparently
violating Geneva conventions that forbid exposing POWs to ``public
curiosity.''
   Each day, Iran's state-run television, monitored in Cyprus,
shows Iraqi POWs in spotless fatigues singing the praises of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and denouncing President Saddam Hussein
of Iraq.
   Iraq, in turn, has taken reporters to POW camps and displayed
Iranian prisoners knitting portraits of Saddam and praising his
wisdom and fair treatment.
   For such prisoners, the prospect of returning to their families
will be balanced against fear of their own governments, who would
likely question them closely and for some time about the conditions
of their capture and imprisonment.
   ``People assuming they'll be instantly reunited with their kids
will be disappointed,'' the European diplomat said.
   Diplomats say many POWs may choose to stay with the country that
captured them rather than return to an uncertain fate. Red Cross
rules forbid the repatriation of prisoners against their will.
   Tehran newspaper said that at least 20,000 Iraqis have opted to
stay in Iran.
   But diplomats said that getting prisoners back is a relatively
low priority for Baghdad, which is more interested in assuring a
lasting peace and ending Iranian support for Kurdish rebels
fighting Iraq's government.
   ``The priority would be on more essential issues, such as the
establishment of ... a durable peace,'' another diplomat said.
   An early return of prisoners bearing tales of mistreatment could
damage the peace talks in Geneva unless both countries,
uncharacteristically, play down such reports.
   Diplomats said the prisoner exchange may be snarled not only by
arguments about those who choose to stay, but by uncertainty over
how many each side holds and by their fate.
   Iran halted Red Cross visits to its 15 known POW camps after Red
Cross officials in 1984 witnessed a prison riot in which guards
killed several POWs.
   The Iranians allowed the visits to resume in 1986, but the Red
Cross found that more than 7,300 previously listed prisoners had
disappeared off the rolls. Tehran said they had chosen to live in
Iran.
   The Red Cross itself suspended visits earlier this year because
it alleged it was unable to visit all prisoners.
</TEXT>
