<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RogerRabbitRaid 1stLd-Writethru a0407 08-27 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roger Rabbit Raid, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0407,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raid Of Apparel Company Nets Alleged Counterfeit T-Shirts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The T-shirts ...,' to DELETE erroneous
question mark in movie title; SUBS last graf to fix typo in title.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A raid by federal marshals and lawyers for
The Walt Disney Co. netted about 2,000 T-shirts featuring allegedly
counterfeit likenesses of movie character Roger Rabbit and Disney
cartoon characters, authorities say.
   The T-shirts and other materials bearing the likenesses of the
star of ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' in addition to Mickey and
Minnie Mouse, Donald Duck and Goofy, were seized Thursday when
lawyers from Hammond, Chicago and New York inspected the goods
during a sidewalk sale by C&D Wholesale apparel company.
   The seizure occurred the same day the Disney Co. and Amblin
Entertainment Inc. filed suit in U.S. District Court against Roger
and Carol Carrier, owners of C&D Wholesale, for alleged copyright
violations and unfair competition.
   The suit seeks an injunction preventing further manufacture or
sale of the T-shirts. Disney and Amblin Entertainment also seek all
profits realized from the sale of the shirts, as well as damages,
lawyers' fees and other costs.
   Amblin is owned by producer Steven Spielberg, who teamed up with
Disney to produce ``Roger Rabbit.'' Also represented at the raid
was The Great Southern Co. of Macon, Ga., which is licensed by
Disney to make T-shirts bearing its designs.
   It was the second such raid in the past three weeks against
alleged unauthorized Roger Rabbit merchandise, said Chuck Champlin,
a spokesman for the filmmaker.
   An Aug. 8 raid of a Milwaukee firm yielded 2,362 shirts and 16
screens used to make them, he said.
   Characters from ``Roger Rabbit'' are licensed jointly by Disney
and Amblin to 40 companies that make more than 500 products.
</TEXT>
