<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks Bjt   08-27 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, Bjt,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Iraq Talks Recess; Problems Reported Over Border Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Iraq-POWs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. secretary-general called a recess today
in the Iran-Iraq peace talks after negotiations faltered. Sources
said problems arose when Iraq insisted on redrawing the southern
border between the warring nations.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said he hoped both
sides would be more flexible when they return to the bargaining
table Sunday. He refused to comment on reports of problems.
   ``It is too early to ask for flexibility,'' he said Friday after
six hours of separate and joint sessions with both sides. ``We are
making progress slowly, but we are trying.''
   The talks began Thursday and are the first in eight years
between Iran and Iraq. They are aimed at consolidating a fragile
cease-fire that began Aug. 20 and at reaching a comprehensive peace
settlement.
   ``In all these exchanges today, many points have been clarified,
and I hope that on Sunday, after the day of reflection (Saturday),
perhaps the flexibility will start,'' Perez de Cuellar told
reporters.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, and his Iraqi
counterpart, Tariq Aziz, met in separate sessions for two hours in
the morning and in a face-to-face plenary meeting for four hours in
the afternoon.
   Diplomatic sources said both sides set forth their often
divergent positions on numerous, intractable subjects, from the
border dispute to exchange of prisoners.
   Velayati gave the first public indication of a problem when he
told reporters after the morning session that a settlement requires
observance of the 1975 Algiers Treaty.
   The treaty made the southern boundary between Iran and Iraq the
middle of the Shatt-al-Arab waterway and granted Iran its claim to
the eastern half. The waterway is Iraq's only access to the sea at
the Persian Gulf.
   In 1980, President Saddam Hussein of Iraq repudiated the treaty.
Five days later, on Sept. 22, the Iraqi army invaded Iran.
   Iran says the treaty still is valid under international law.
   The treaty is a crucial issue in the peace talks because a U.N.
peace resolution calls for a troop withdrawal to internationally
recognized boundaries.
   Iraq says the boundaries are in dispute and seeks renegotiation
of them.
   Sources close to the Iranian delegation said the Iraqi side was
insisting the cease-fire line be drawn so as to give Iraq control
of the waterway.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Iraq also
was pressing for early dredging by the United Nations of the
waterway, heavily silted after eight years of war and impassable
because of sunken ships.
   Neither Velayati nor Aziz spoke to reporters after the session
Friday night.
   While the talks were under way, Iraqi Kurds demonstrated in
front of the U.N. building to protest the reported continued use of
chemical weapons by Baghdad against the rebellious minority.
   In New York, meanwhile, the Security Council denounced the use
of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war, especially attacks
against Iran by Iraq.
   Before the talks began, Perez de Cuellar told reporters that the
bitterness and historic hostility between the two sides was such
that it would be difficult to continue the face-to-face
discussions, which began Thursday.
   ``I don't think that (continuing) face-to-face is possible so
far,'' he said. ``We have to be a little patient. It is too early
for (two sides) alone face-to-face and even face-to-face with me
would be very difficult,'' he said.
   The Friday session began with both sides meeting in separate
chambers and U.N. officials shuttling between them.
   But in the afternoon, they returned to the spacious Council
Chamber and addressed each other directly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
