<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0998</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bill Cosby has said no to a
county request to make up for a $10,000 budget cut by the
administration of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis in a program aimed at
preventing teen-age pregnancy.
   Franklin County Commission Chairman William Benson said
frustration and anger at state officials prompted commissioners to
seek the donation from Cosby, who lives in the county in nearby
Shelburne Falls.
   ``It's one thing to say that money is tight. It's another thing
to have to approach a local celebrity, hat in hand, just to keep
alive a program that was supposed to be a priority of the
governor,'' Benson said Thursday.
   The $10,000 grant for the program was among $40,000 cut from
county allocations in the state's fiscal 1989 budget following
projected revenue shortfalls.
   In a letter to county commissioners this week, an aide to Cosby
said the comedian would not cover the state aid cut.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Sonny Bono says he has been
flying first- class for 30 years. Now he wants the city to foot the
bill so his wife and infant son can travel the world with him as he
promotes this desert resort _ first-class.
   Bono called a news conference Thursday to explain his reasons
for the request so it doesn't blow up into what he called a
``national incident.''
   Bono, who makes $15,000 a year as mayor, said he has flown
first-class since his days as an entertainer and as part of the
husband-and-wife singing duo Sonny and Cher.
   ``I am a family man. I don't want to go away and not see my kid
for 10 days,'' Bono said of his 4-month-old son, Chesare Elan.
``That may sound corny or ridiculous, but I take him everywhere I
go. And I also want to travel with my wife.''
   Some residents have criticized the request, which comes at a
fiscally sensitive time. Palm Springs voters will decide Nov. 8
whether to continue a utility tax to avoid a deficit.
   ``I'm just throwing it out there. If the public doesn't want it
and they say, `No, you can't travel that way,' then so be it,''
Bono said.
   City spokeswoman Julie Baumer said there are no provisions for
city officials to fly first-class or for spouses to accompany
officials on trips.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of well-wishers flocked to a downtown club
to help celebrate the 80th birthday of famed ornithologist Roger
Tory Peterson, whose ``Field Guide to the Birds'' has become a
bible for millions of bird watchers.
   Peterson, who turns 80 Sunday, recalled Friday that it was a
seventh-grade teacher in Jamestown, N.Y., who got him interested in
birds by having his class form a junior Audubon Club.
   Peterson also remembered that his original ``Field Guide to the
Birds'' was turned down by four publishers before Houghton Mifflin
Co. of Boston accepted the manuscript. First published in 1934, the
book has since become one of the company's biggest sellers.
Houghton Mifflin threw the reception.
   In the decades since, the internationally known author, artist
and lecturer has written, illustrated or edited a succession of
bird guides, flower guides and other nature books.
   Among his many honors, Peterson has received a Medal of Freedom.
   Peterson said he was ``angry and scared'' about growing old and
owes Houghton Mifflin five more books.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter John Denver has denied
reports that he would pay the Soviet Union $10 million to take a
ride on a Soviet space ship, but he still would like to go.
   ``Let me be clear: I would give my guitar to go into space,''
Denver said Friday. ``I've expressed this to NASA. Unfortunately,
it looks like a civilian in the American space program is now a
long way off. To fly with the Soviets greatly enhances what I
already considered an incredible opportunity.''
   He said the commercial arm of the Soviet space program
approached him about being the first American civilian to go up in
a Soviet spacecraft. Last April, Denver said he traveled to Moscow
to discuss the proposal with Soviet officials and learned ``that it
costs them roughly $10 million to house, train and ultimately put a
human in space for one week.''
   ``In the past, when a non-civilian foreigner has gone up in a
Soviet spacecraft, these costs have been assumed by means of a
government-to-government agreement. Since this venture is
non-governmental, alternative means of financing will have to be
explored.
   ``Regardless of what has been implied elsewhere, I have no
intention of paying the Soviets $10 million and I think it would be
highly inappropriate to do so.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Designer hats for horses may be the next fashion
trend on New York City streets, says Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   Koch told the Industrial Designers Society of America on Friday
that he's been looking into ways to comfort the city's carriage
horses during hot, muggy weather.
   City regulations require that the animals be taken back to their
stables when the mercury reaches 90 degrees, but animal lovers say
the horses can experience discomfort in temperatures just below
that. One horse collapsed earlier this month while being taken to
his stable on a 90-degree-plus day.
   ``We've looked into the question of having umbrellas of
different sorts to safeguard the horses and we've discarded that as
unworkable,'' Koch told the designers. ``We've come up with
something that goes back to our roots, I guess _ a straw hat for a
horse.''
   He said there is no official design contest for such a hat, but
``if anyone wants to send me a drawing ... I will select the best
hat and then (Parks Commissioner) Henry Stern will issue
regulations.''
</TEXT>
