<HEAD>Defense Ministry Says Two Peasants Killed In Contra Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels attacked a remote
village in southeastern Nicaragua, killing two peasants and
wounding three others, the Defense Ministry said.
   The ministry said in a report Friday that the attack occurred
Wednesday in the village of El Amparo, 16 miles north of the Costa
Rican border. It said one of those killed was a 7-year-old girl.
   President Daniel Ortega said Wednesday that a total of 28,067
people have been killed and 26,486 wounded since the U.S.-supported
Contra rebels launched their war against the leftist Sandinista
government 7{ years ago.
   The Sandinista government and the Contras agreed March 21 to
halt offensive military operations. A cease-fire pact signed two
days later failed to advance beyond talks on a permanent truce.
   Negotiations broke off June 9 and each side has charged the
other with violating the cease-fire.
