<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Guatemala     08-27 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Refuses To Let Rebels Take Part In National Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Vinicio Cerezo said the main
leftist rebel coalition must put down its weapons before being
allowed to participate in a planned national dialogue aimed at
ending 30 years of civil war.
   Cerezo, who has been under fire from the powerful right for even
considering talks with the rebels, said in a statement Friday that
``only groups and organizations within the law'' can participate in
the dialogue.
   He urged the Guatemalan Revolutionary Union to ``understand the
human cost of a 30-year confrontation'' and to avoid a ``blood
bath.''
   Mongsignor Rodolfo Quezada Toruno, head of the national
reconciliation commission, said the rebels told him at a meeting in
Costa Rica this week that they won't lay down their arms prior to
the talks.
   The dialogue is scheduled to begin next month.
   The Revolutionary Union is a coalition of three leftist
guerrilla groups.
   Cerezo's one meeting with the rebels _ last year in Spain under
the terms of a Central American peace plan _ sparked a storm of
criticism from the right. He has since survived an attempted
military coup.
   Cerezo pointed out in his communique that the regional peace
plan gives the rebels the option of asking for political amnesty in
return for laying down their arms.
   Revolutionary Union leaders have said they won't do this until
there is a clear sign that the government is ready to address the
sharp economic and political inequalities in Guatemala.
   The rebel leaders are currently on a Central American tour that
includes meetings with the presidents of Nicaragua and Costa Rica
and high-level meetings in Honduras and El Salvador.
   The presidents of those nations, in addition to Guatemala,
signed the regional peace accord last summer. It is aimed at ending
wars in the region through negotiations and also calls for
democratization and amnesties for political prisoners.
</TEXT>
