<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EducationAwards     08-27 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Education Awards,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NOW Unit Criticizes Bennett, Other Education And Sports Figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William Bennett, a
University of Michigan dean and others have been cited as people in
key positions who exhibit ``sluggish and unenlightened behavior''
by blocking educational fairness, according to a feminist group.
   The Project on Equal Educational Rights, an arm of the National
Organization for Women on Friday named them winners of its annual
``silver snail'' awards.
   Bennett who has been an annual ``silver snail'' winner since the
inception of the awards in 1985, was inducted into the``Snail Hall
of Fame'' this year.
   PEER cited, among other things, his criticism of Stanford
University's decision to integrate literature by women, minorities
and non-Westerners into its core curriculum.
   Peter Steiner, dean of the School of Literature, Science and the
Arts at U-M in Ann Arbor, received a snail award ``for his failure
to promote affirmative action at the University of Michigan and for
denigrating the academic potential of black students,'' said PEER
Director Eleanor Hinton Hoytt.
   According to PEER, Steiner told his faculty last September that
he did not want to change the university into ``another kind of
institution where minorities would naturally flock in much greater
numbers'' and in January said that ``perhaps something in the
environment leads blacks ... to be less willing to invest the time
in college.''
   A University of Michigan spokesman did not immediately return a
call requesting comment.
   But PEER gave its highest and most positive award to Rollin
Haffer, a Port Jefferson, N.Y., physical education teacher who sued
Temple University to win equal athletic opportunities for women at
the school.
   The out-of-court settlement reached last June after an
eight-year legal battle ``represents a major advance in the fight
to achieve equality for women in intercollegiate athletics,'' said
Haffer's attorney, Ellen Vargyas.
   Greg Hlibok also received an award for leading the Gallaudet
College student body in protests that eventually resulted in
selection of the school's first deaf president and a board of
directors for the school with a majority of deaf members.
   Others honored included Bret Weinstein, a University of
Pennsylvania freshman who exposed sexual and racial exploitation at
a fraternity ``mystery party''; Albert R. Killackey, an El Monte,
Calif., parent who got his school district to eliminate what he
considered discriminatory mother-daughter and father-son banquets
for youngsters; and Julie Croteau, a Manassas, Va. teen-ager who
sued her school's coaches after she failed to make the varsity
baseball team.
   Other ``snail'' awards went to CBS sports commentators Billy
Packer and Dick Stockton, Houston Astros pitcher Bob Knepper and
officials at Northwestern State University of Louisiana for what
PEER cited as oensive remarks or publications about female amateur
and professional athletes.
</TEXT>
