<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-27 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Employment Rate At Record High; Blacks Show No Improvement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department says youth employment is
showing signs of paralleling the generally positive U.S. employment
outlook, with young workers this summer experiencing the lowest
unemployment rate since 1969.
   A record 68.5 percent of the nation's youths have jobs, the
department said Friday.
   The unemployment rate among workers aged 16-24 was 10.9 percent
in July compared with 11.7 percent a year ago, the department said.
   However the good news was tempered with figures showing all of
the improvement was among whites. Blacks did not share in any of
it, the government said. Only about half of the nation's black
youths have jobs this summer, compared with three-fourths of white
youths.
   The jobless rate for white youths in July was 8.9 percent,
compared with 9.7 percent a year earlier. The rate among black
youths was almost three times higher _ 25.3 percent, the same as in
July 1987.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ag Department Warns Drought-Stricken Farmers They Can't Collect
Twice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers suffering drought losses will not be
allowed to collect on the same loss twice even if they are eligible
for benefits under more than one Agriculture Department program,
officials said.
   Undersecretary Roland R. Vautour said Friday that if a farmer
has a crop loss that would qualify him for ongoing emergency
livestock feed provisions and the new disaster payment program, he
cannot double up on the benefits.
   The basic restrictions are spelled out by the Disaster
Assistance Act of 1988 which went into effect Friday. However
Vautour the regulations and operating procedures which will
implement the statutory provisions have not been completed.
   ``Producers should start assembling their sales receipts and
other data to substantiate their actual production information,''
he said.
   Department officials have said they hope to begin actual
operation of the $3.9 billion drought-aid law by Oct. 1. At that
time, they hope, farmers can begin applying at country offices of
the department's Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation
Service for benefits.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Navy To Begin Random Drug Testing Of Civilian Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has announced it will begin random
drug testing of selected civilian employees this fall.
   The service said on Friday that Navy Secretary William Ball
signed its final plan for the tests on Aug. 6 and it had begun
notifying 81,000 of the Navy's 337,000 civilian workers they will
be subject to urinalysis testing for drugs.
   Testing legally could begin as early as Oct. 6, said Navy
spokesman Lt. Ken Ross, but Ross said the service does not plan to
start the program until early November.
   The Navy follows the Army which is already is testing civilian
workers in sensitive positions, to become the second military
service to launch a testing program for civilian workers. The Air
Force still is working on its testing guidelines.
   All of the military services have long tested men and women on
active duty.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activists Campaign to Release South Korean Political Prisoners.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. peace activists are calling for the
release of all political prisoners in South Korea and the
withdrawal of the 45,000 American troops stationed there following
the arrests of two Americans at a rally in Seoul.
   Susan Bailey of the People's Anti-War Mobilization, a New
York-based group that opposes the U.S. military presence in South
Korea, announced Friday the group was stepping up its efforts and
forming an international campaign.
   Bailey and another American, Charles Scheiner, were arrested
Aug. 20 at a rally held five days earlier by supporters of the
movement to unify North and South Korea.
   ``I was surrounded by plainclothes police on foot,'' Bailey
said. ``They began screaming at us, forcibly grabbed us, picked us
up and threw us in the back seat of unmarked cars.''
   Bailey maintains that she and Scheiner were held by the Seoul
Metropolitan Police and by immigration authorities for 55 hours
without being allowed to contact U.S. Embassy officials, and then
were deported without being charged with a crime.
   South Korean government officials told embassy representatives
that Bailey and Scheiner violated laws prohibiting tourists from
participating in political demonstrations, according to the State
Department.
