<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Hungary     08-27 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Hungary,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Foreign Minister Says Communist Attempt A Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's foreign minister said
Soviet-backed efforts to build a communist society in Afghanistan
failed, so the country wants to introduce a multiparty system and
mixed economy.
   Foreign Minister Abdul Vakil also said Friday that Pakistan,
which supports the Afghan guerrillas, has a ``subversive attitude''
that threatens the success of an accord calling for the withdrawal
of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   ``We once thought socialism could be built in Afghanistan, but
this was a theory that proved wrong,'' Vakil said at a news
conference. ``The country has had a feudal, traditional tribal
system, and socialism is a luxury in such a backward state.''
   He added, ``State ownership of property is under 20 percent,
public ownership of land under 1 percent. How could one build
socialism amid such circumstances? We have no funds for that.''
   ``A multiparty system and a mixed economy is the choice of our
people. We have failed with the land reform, with the obliteration
of illiteracy, our reforms were rash and ran across national and
tribal feelings,'' Vakil said.
   While admitting failure to establish a one-party communist
state, Vakil did not criticize the Soviet military intervention in
Afghanistan in Dec. 1979.
   Soviet troops entered to back the Afghan government in its war
with Moslem guerrillas, who are based in Pakistan.
   Under a U.N.-mediated accord reached in Geneva in April, the
Soviet troops began withdrawing May 15 and are to be out of the
country by Feb. 15.
   ``Only three months have passed since the signing of the Geneva
agreements, and there are another seven left,'' Vakil said. ``We do
hope that the United Nations and other international bodies will be
able to see that order returns in that respect. If not, we shall
take joint steps with the Soviet Union.''
   He did not elaborate.
   While Soviet troops have withdrawn already from 25 of the
country's 30 provinces, Vakil said, none of the provinces could be
taken over by ``the armed extremists'' fighting government troops.
   He pledged the Kabul government would pursue ``the policy of
national reconciliation'' and stop further bloodshed. ``But where
rockets are fired at us, we retaliate firmly,'' he said.
   Vakil said his government is striving for a dialogue with the
opposition, the aim being a broad-based coalition government.
   ``Pakistan itself agreed to this ... If it continues its
subversive attitude, the Geneva accords' spirit and content could
be eroded,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
