<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AngolaTalks     08-27 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola Talks,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks End Without Agreement On Cuban Withdrawal; More Talks
Scheduled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest round of talks on the
future of Angola and South-West Africa left unresolved the key
question of a timetable for the withdrawal of Cuban troops from
Angola.
   The delegates agreed Friday to return to Brazzaville the week of
Sept. 5 for more meetings after adjourning the latest negotiations,
which began Wednesday.
   Cuba and Angola have said the withdrawal process for the 50,000
Cuban troops from Angola will take four years. The South Africans
want the withdrawal to be linked to their own withdrawal from
South-West Africa, due to be completed by June 1989.
   South Africa rules South-West Africa _ also known as Namibia _
under a disputed mandate.
   A joint statement issued by the Angolan, Cuban and South African
delegations and the American mediators described the talks as
serious, detailed and constructive.
   An American diplomat close to the U.S. delegation said a Sept. 1
target date for agreement on the Cuban withdrawal timetable was not
applicable now.
   ``There is a substantial set of differences of perspective on
some issues. The parties come here with a certain view of the
situation: it isn't just a blank check,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   He refused to speculate on the content of specific proposals but
said the differences between the two sides can be resolved.
   Earlier Friday, sources in the South African delegation said
substantial progress had been made on the Cuban withdrawal issue.
They said the United States proposed the Cubans pull out within 18
months, a compromise the Angolan delegation took home to Luanda for
consideration by its government.
   Angola's ambassador to West Germany, Herminio Escorcio, told
reporters on emerging from the talks: ``It is a question of
flexibility on the part of South Africa and the United States,''
who both support the Angolan rebels.
   On the question of continuing U.S. support for anti-Marxist
UNITA guerrillas, which was raised earlier in the week by President
Eduardo dos Santos of Angola, the American diplomat said this was
obviously on delegates' minds but was not on the agenda.
   The South African-backed UNITA guerrillas led by Jonas Savimbi
are fighting to overthrow the Angolan government. UNITA has not
been involved in the Brazzaville talks and has ignored a cease-fire
signed by South Africa, Angola and Cuba.
   When asked if the United States was under pressure over its
support for UNITA, the American diplomat said, ``It can't be a
bargaining chip. It's absurd to ask us to unilaterally disengage. I
don't consider it a condition of our mediation (at the talks).
There are no conditions on our acting as mediators in that way.''
</TEXT>
