<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VincennesTape Bjt   08-27 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vincennes Tape, Bjt,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Video Of Shoot-Down Shows Tension, Elation Among Crew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy videotape made aboard the USS Vincennes
during the battle that led to the accidental downing of an Iranian
airliner shows a tense crew that rejoices when it thinks it has
shot down a fighter plane.
   ``That was a dead-on!'' shouted a crewman, moments after the
missile roared into the sky aboard the Persian Gulf. ``Direct hit
on the airplane?'' asked someone. ``Yes,'' another replied.
   But within 10 minutes, the crew members appeared ``bewildered
and solemn'' after learning the missile had shot down a civilian
airliner instead of an Iranian F-14, NBC-TV reported. All 290
people aboard the jet died.
   The tape, made by a Navy camera team during the July 3 incident,
was obtained by NBC through the Freedom of Information Act and
shown Friday on its ``Nightly News.'' It also was broadcast on
other networks.
   A U.S. Defense Department investigation found that the Vincennes
crew had misinterpreted radar and electronic signals emitted from
the Iranian Airbus A-300.
   The investigators blamed human error by the crew, but Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Iran bore a heavy responsibility
since it allowed the jetliner to fly over the area while a sea
battle raged below.
   Carlucci said no Navy personnel will be disciplined.
   The tape shows the Vincennes crew training their binoculars on
distant Iranian gunboats at the start of the battle. ``One appears
to be going out to starboard and one's in the middle,'' called out
someone.
   ``Coming inbound fast. The one at 3-5-0 is inbound,'' said
another. ``There she goes!'' shouted someone else.
   During the ensuing fight with the gunboats, which used the
5-inch guns mounted on deck, one crewman yelled, ``I don't know
where it's hitting.''
   ``Come on, let's keep it down,'' said another over the din of
the radio transmissions and firing of the guns.
   In the tape, a crewman stared intently at a green radar screen,
a supervisor paced back and forth, and someone called out the
positions of the approaching vessels.
   Then the missiles blast off from the ship's deck. A crewman
wearing earphones shouted, ``Oh, dead!'' Three other crewmen
gathered around him, and he shouted ``That was a dead-on!''
   ``Relax,'' shouted someone. ``Keep the noise down,'' another
person yelled. ``Knock it off,'' ordered another.
   ``Direct hit on the airplane?'' asked someone. ``Yes,'' another
replied.
   Within 10 minutes, the crew of the Aegis-class crusier, which
contains the Navy's most sophisticated electronic warfare
equipment, realized it had shot down an airliner, and began a
futile search for survivors, NBC reported.
   The Defense Department's report said several of the crew's
assumptions about the approaching flight were wrong, including that
it was descending toward the Vincennes and flying outside a
commercial air corridor.
   Iran has rejected U.S. claims it was partly responsible for the
tragedy, saying the Navy's presence in the Persian Gulf was to
blame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
