<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle-Guard     08-27 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Guard,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Guard Releases Records, Former Guardsmen Play Down Quayle
AWOL</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana National Guard officials have
released records that indicate Dan Quayle was absent without leave
during his last drill meeting, but former unit members downplayed
seriousness of the offense.
   ``It wasn't like walking off the front lines,''said Michael
Tropp, a former member of Quayle's public information unit. ``But
obviously AWOL in the Guard meant that you weren't where you were
supposed to be.''
   The Republican vice presidential candidate has been dogged in
recent days by accusations he used his prominent family's
connections to gain a position at the Guard's headquarters
detachment at the height of the Vietnam War.
   Capt. Cathi Kiger, a spokeswoman for the National Guard, said
Quayle's record of service was solid.
   ``It appears Senator Quayle mised two drills in six years. We
can still consider his attendance very good,'' said Kiger, who
released the documents Friday. ``If you missed five drills you were
ordered into active duty.''
   ``The smart ones obviously didn't do it more than five times,''
Tropp said in a telephone interview from his Sturgis, Mich., home.
   ``His attendance record was perfectly acceptable,'' Quayle
spokesman Jeff Nesbit said Friday from his Washington, D.C.,
office. ``He did miss the last weekend, but that was fairly common.
I don't think it's an issue.''
   The morning report for the May 1975 drill _ the last in which
Quayle participated _ shows a second unit member was absent in
addition to Quayle.
   Kiger said enlisted men who had fewer than the allowed five
absences during their stint occasionally did not show up for their
final drill weekend.
   ``You did your six years and said, `Good bye,' '' Kiger said.
   Lt. Timothy R. Sendak, a member of Quayle's unit, said he did
not recall AWOL absences as being particularly commonplace in the
Guard.
   ``It just didn't happen that often,'' said Sendak, who stressed
he was unfamiliar with circumstances of Quayle's absence. ``If a
regulation was broken, it was broken.''
   But both Sendak and Jon D. Perry, another member of the unit,
said commanders took special circumstances into account.
   ``Most of the people in the unit were professionals, and from
time-to-time provisions were made,'' said Perry, of Bloomington,
Ind. ``We all had occasions when there was some kind of conflict.''
   Sendak added, ``It was quite common for Guardsmen or reservists
to take time and make it up later.''
   The records further confirmed both that the headquarters
detachment was under strength when Quayle enlisted in May 1969 and
that a slot was available at the time he transferred into the
command's public information unit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
