<DOCNO> AP880827-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Politics     08-27 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Politics,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Announces New Opposition Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel
launched a new opposition movement today to challenge President
Corazon Aquino, claiming Mrs. Aquino will lead the country to
``national disaster'' if she remains in power.
   ``I accept the honor and the challenge to lead a coalesced
opposition against a blundering and immoral administration that has
betrayed the people,'' Laurel said in announcing formation of the
Union for National Action.
   The Union's platform calls for a new treaty on the status of
American military bases in the Philippines that would provide for a
gradual phasing out of the facilities.
   The vice president said his movement will serve as a watchdog on
government action and will expose alleged corruption.
   ``I am relieved that I no longer have to stand up beside the
president,'' said Laurel, chairman of the Union. ``If she continues
to run the government, the country is headed for national
disaster.''
   Laurel was joined at the Union's inaugural news conference by
Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile and leaders of several opposition groups,
including the New Society Movement of ousted President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino ran under the banner of Laurel's United Nationalist
   Democratic Organization in February 1986 elections that led to
Marcos' ouster after 20 years in power.
   
   Two weeks ago, Laurel accused Mrs. Aquino of incompetence and
urged her to resign to make way for new elections, but he received
little popular support. Mrs. Aquino vowed to remain in office until
the end of her term in 1992.
   There was no immediate reaction from the president to formation
of the Union.
   The announcement by Laurel and Enrile was the latest in a series
of attempts to build a viable opposition movement. Previous
attempts have foundered because of personal rivalries.
   Enrile is the only opposition figure in the 23-member Senate,
and Laurel's political fortunes have been declining since
September, when he resigned as foreign secretary and refused to
serve in the Cabinet.
   Manila newspapers reported this month that 21 of 22 members of
Laurel's party in the House of Representatives were defecting to
pro-Aquino parties. Many members left the party last year.
   Enrile, fired as defense minister on Nov. 23, 1986, after a
failed coup by his followers, said the country was facing the
deepest crisis of its history because of ``a crisis of leadership.''
   Enrile, vice chairman of the Union, said opposition groups
rallied behind Laurel ``not for the self-interest of any one of us
... but above all to avert a potential, possible national tragedy.''
   In a statement to reporters, the Union called for negotiating a
new treaty with the United States on the status of American
military bases after their lease expires in 1991. The coalition
said a new treaty should be limited to 10 years and provide for
gradual phasing out of the six bases.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to say whether she would support a new
bases treaty.
   The Union also called for replacing the U.S.-style presidential
government with a parliamentary system.
   Mrs. Aquino abolished the unicameral legislative system imposed
by Marcos and replaced it with a Senate and House of
Representatives, returning to the system in force before the former
president declared eight years of martial law in 1972.
   The Union statement also called for stepping up the fight
against communist insurgents but offered to legalize the Communist
Party of the Philippines if it disavowed violence. The government
has made similar offers in the past.
   Mrs. Aquino originally named Laurel as prime minister of her
government but abolished the post soon afterward. Laurel had
complained since then that he was shunted aside by Mrs. Aquino's
advisers.
   Today's announcement came the day before the first anniversary
of the bloody Aug. 28, 1987, coup attempt, led by Enrile's former
protege, Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan. Honasan escaped from detention
last April and remains at large.
   The coup attempt was the strongest and most dangerous of the
half dozen attempts to topple the Aquino government. At least 53
people were killed and hundreds were wounded.
</TEXT>
