<HEAD>U.S. Fighter Jets Allegedly Violate Barbados Airspace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several American fighter jets
allegedly violated the airspace of this Caribbean island and
ignored orders by local air traffic controllers to leave,
newspapers and radio stations said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said the reports Friday were being
investigated.
   Ham radio operators, who reported the incident to the local
press, monitored conversations between five jet pilots and air
traffic controllers on Wednesday and said the jets refused orders
to leave Barbadian airspace, the state-owned Caribbean Broadcasting
Corp. said.
   ``We have been informed by the Barbados government of an alleged
violation of its airspace by American aircraft,'' U.S. Embassy
Information Officer Mathew McGrath told The Associated Press.
   ``They (Barbadian officials) called us in to discuss the matter.
We are examining the report,'' he said.
   He said the aircraft carrier USS Independence passed near
Barbados, en route to San Diego from Norfolk Va. He would not say
if the jets that allegedly violated the airspace came from the
Independence.
   U.S. Embassy Charge d'Affaires John Clark met for 20 minutes
with Foreign Affairs Minister James Tudor on Thursday, said
McGrath. McGrath refused to say if Barbados made a formal complaint
to Tudor.
