<1ST_LINE>u a PM-YonkersDeseg Bjt   08-27 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Stays in Contempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yonkers officials, continuing to defy a
housing desegregation plan upheld by a federal appeals court, plan
to ask the Supreme Court for relief from up to $1 million a day in
fines that could bankrupt the city.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Friday reaffirmed the
fines imposed by U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand against this
community just north of New York City. The fines had been stayed
pending the appeals court's ruling.
   The panel also upheld $500-a-day personal fines and the threat
of jail against four city councilmen found in contempt for refusing
to endorse the desegregation plan mandated by Sand.
   However, the court softened the fines against New York's
fourth-largest city, setting a $1 million-a-day cap instead of
letting them double each day as under the original order.
Otherwise, the three-judge panel said, the fines would reach
``unreasonable proportions.''
   The court also delayed reimposing the fines until Sept. 2,
allowing the city to seek a further stay of the penalty and a
chance to appeal the case to the nation's highest court.
   An appeal is planned, City Manager Neil DeLuca said.
   A few hours after the ruling, the seven-member City Council held
a weekly meeting to give the four recalcitrant councilmen a chance
to change their votes.
   But the four stuck to their position for the third time, making
the vote 4-3 against the plan.
   ``What I see here is the manipulation by the judiciary of a
legislative body,'' said one of the four, Councilman Henry
Spallone. ``I believe this is a miscarriage of justice.''
   The appeals court upheld the threat of imprisonment against the
councilmen after the 10th day of the penalties if they continue
blocking the plan.
   Councilman Nicholas Longo said the only reason there were any
``yes'' votes was ``intimidation and fear'' by the court.
   Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko told those attending the meeting that he
voted for the plan because he feared a contempt citation.
   The fines Sand imposed against the city Aug. 2 started at $100
but doubled daily and would have wiped out the city's $337 million
annual budget in less than a month.
   The fines and the countdown to the councilmen's jail time were
suspended Aug. 9 when the city and the councilmen appealed to the
2nd Circuit. The councilmen had been scheduled to go to jail Aug.
11.
   By Aug. 9, the city had paid $12,700 in fines and each
councilman had paid $3,500.
   Under the new timetable, Yonkers would pay $12,800 next Friday
and would reach the $1-million-a-day cap a week after that, at
which time the city would have paid more than $2.6 million in all.
The fines would be $1 million each day after that.
   Though Yonkers' budget for the year would be wiped out in about
11 months, the city would face bankruptcy long before that. A state
agency, the Financial Control Board, has taken over the city's
pursestrings, imposing spending restrictions and drafting a
worst-case plan.
   Secretary of State Gail Shaffer, who heads the control board,
said the state's declaration of a fiscal crisis would continue
``until the City Council acts to purge the city of its contempt.''
   Sand's contempt ruling was the most serious step in his
continuing battle to impose a plan to build hundreds of subsidized
apartments in Yonkers' predominantly white neighborhoods. That plan
stemmed from his 1985 landmark ruling that Yonkers had deliberately
segregated housing and schools for four decades.
   About 24 percent of the city's 200,000 residents are black or
Hispanic. The city is divided by highways that the courts have
ruled serve as racial barriers.
   Sand imposed the fines after the council refused, 4-3, to
endorse the housing plan by approving incentives for 800 units of
low cost housing throughout Yonkers.
   The vote reversed the council's 5-2 approval in January of the
same proposal, which the city had agreed to as part of a consent
decree.
</TEXT>
