<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MercChief     08-27 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Merc Chief,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman Of New York Mercantile Exchange Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Bradt, chairman of the New York
Mercantile Exchange, has resigned after the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission found he had acted inappropriately.
   The commission did not accuse Bradt of any illegal activity, nor
did it recommend he resign. An internal exchange inquiry in January
cleared Bradt of any wrongdoing.
   Bradt submitted his resignation Thursday night after a meeting
in which members of the Merc's board discussed the findings of the
commission's report. In today's editions, The New York Times quoted
unidentified sources close to the exchange as saying no vote on
whether Bradt should be ousted was taken at that meeting.
   Bradt, 42, became chairman of the Merc in March 1987. In a
statement issued late Thursday he said: ``I am pleased with the
findings contained in the C.F.T.C. report that at no time were any
exchange or C.F.T.C. rules or regulations violated. However, I
believe it is in the best interest of my business, my family and
the exchange, now that I have been vindicated, to step down as
chairman.''
   The Merc is the world's largest crude oil futures exchange. The
commission report followed an investigation that the exchange began
in November 1987 after exchange members accused Bradt and Kevin P.
Conway, then vice president for compliance, of improper business
relationships.
   The central issue concerned talks between the two men about
establishing a clearing business at the exchange. A clearing
business processes trades for fees.
   In January, the exchange board cleared Bradt of wrongdoing.
Conway, a lawyer, was dismissed and could face disbarment
proceedings.
   During Bradt's tenure, he clashed with fellow board members over
his desire to merge the Merc with the Commodity Exchange Inc.,
which is the world's largest precious metals futures exchange.
   Zoltan Guttman, 38, vice chairman of the Merc, was named to
succeed Bradt. He will serve out Bradt's two-year term, which
expires in March.
</TEXT>
