<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PatriotismPoll     08-27 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Patriotism Poll,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Many West Germans Indifferent To Hearing National Anthem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germans are about evenly divided
over whether they feel a tingle of pride when they hear their
country's national anthem, according to results of a poll.
   The survey also reported Friday that many university graduates
said they feel ``bothered'' when they hear the national anthem,
which was once called ``Deutschland Ueber Alles'' (Germany Above
Everything) but is now known simply as ``Deutschlandlied'' (German
Hymn).
   ``Deutschland Ueber Alles'' was a well-known symbol of Nazi
might under Adolf Hitler. The tune is still the country's national
anthem, but stanzas that moved millions of people to militant
fervor during Nazi times were dropped after World War II.
   According to the poll of 2,078 people conducted by the respected
Ipos surveying institute, 46.5 percent said they felt proud when
they heard the national anthem.
   But 48.3 percent said they felt indifferent or no pride when
hearing the anthem, and 5.2 percent said hearing it bothered them,
the institute reported.
   A total of 12.1 percent of the university graduates polled said
they are bothered when they hear the national anthem, the institute
said.
   The institute did not state the poll's margin of error.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
