<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BRF-BermudaEarthquake     08-27 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Bermuda Earthquake,150</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MENLOW PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusual ``moderate'' sized
earthquake hit in the northern Atlantic Ocean off the coast of
Bermuda on Saturday, officials at the United States Geological
Survey said.
   ``A moderate earthquake centered in the ocean about 80 miles
west of Hamilton, Bermuda struck at 3:05 a.m. EDT,'' said USGS
spokeswoman Pat Jorgenson.
   The quake measured 5.3 on the Richter scale, Jorgenson said. But
she said the USGS has not issued a tidal warning in connection with
the earthquake.
   ``It was felt strongly by the residents of Hamilton,'' she added.
   The USGS said Saturday's earthquake struck in the same area
where another quake hit last June 24. But ``it is unusual for a
quake to hit in the north Atlantic. We have them in the southern
Pacific all the time,'' said one USGS official.
   There was no information immediately available about damages or
injuries, officials said.
</TEXT>
