<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsoon Moisture Lingers In Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front bore down on the upper Mississippi Valley and the
central Plains early today, while thunderstorms in the Southwest
scattered monsoon moisture across the region, with most of the
deluge hitting Nevada and Utah.
   Nellis Air Force Base, near Las Vegas, received more than half
an inch of rain Friday night, while to the north Tonopah also
reported receiving nearly a half inch of rain in 30 minutes. The
downpour caused water to flow across the desert in northwest Clark
County, north of Las Vegas.
   Showers and thunderstorms drifted from southwest Utah into
northeast Arizona on Friday night, accompanied by brief, heavy
rains. Southern Utah reported minor flooding over Beaver County.
Showers and thunderstorms also developed over southern Death Valley.
   Thunderstorms swept through the central Plains into the western
Great Lakes region, with the strongest storms in northern Kansas
and eastern Colorado.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered through eastern
Pennsylvania and the northwest and east-central coasts of Florida.
   Meanwhile, a tropical depression hovered over northeast Cuba,
about 300 miles southeast of Miami, late Friday, moving northwest
at 10 to 15 mph.
   Little change in strength was expected during the night but it
could strengthen today. If the depression is upgraded to a tropical
storm, it will be named Chris.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the upper Great Lakes region through the lower Missouri
Valley, and from the central and southern Plains into the central
Rockies; numerous showers and thunderstorms from upper Michigan
into eastern and southern Wisconsin, and across the Colorado
Rockies; and showers and thunderstorms across northern Arizona and
southern Utah, over Florida and eastern parts of the southern
Atlantic Coast.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 80s or 90s across
much of the nation; in the 70s from the northern and central
Rockies through the middle Missouri Valley into the lower Great
Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley; in the 60s from the northern
Plains into the northern Great Lakes region; from 100 to 105
degrees from the Rio Grande Valley into north central Texas; and
100-110 degrees from the desert Southwest into the California
valleys.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Alpena, Mich., and Butte and Havre, Mont., to 94 degrees
at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 73 fair; Boston 69 foggy; Buffalo 58 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 75 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 61 fair; Cleveland 59
fair; Detroit 60 fair; Miami 83 fair; New York 70 foggy;
Philadelphia 72 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 60 partly cloudy;
Portland, Maine 59 foggy; Washington 72 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 85 partly cloudy;
Denver 70 windy; Des Moines 63 cloudy; Indianapolis 62 partly
cloudy; Kansas City 69 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 65 showery;
Nashville 69 fair; New Orleans 77 hazy; St. Louis 66 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 68 cloudy; Anchorage 54 rain; Las Vegas 74
thunderstorms; Los Angeles 69 partly cloudy; Phoenix 94 cloudy;
Salt Lake City 67 fair; San Diego 70 fair; San Francisco 58 fair;
Seattle 62 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 59 fair; Toronto 54 fair.
</TEXT>
