<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0459 08-27 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Situation in Burma, at a Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Radio Rangoon reports of other prison rioting.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance is a look at protests in Burma:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RALLIES _ Police and government workers in the Taunggyi, the
state capital of Shan, joined 100,000 demonstrators in demanding an
interim government Friday. In Rangoon, Aung Gyi Suu Kyi, daughter
of late independence leader Aung San, told 400,000 cheering people
only immediate democracy could end the unrest.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   STRIKES _ Trains and domestic flights of Union Burma Airways
were halted. Oil refineries were closed at Syriam, across the
Rangoon River, and at Mann in central Burma. Most factories of the
Industries Ministry were crippled. Foreign ships were stranded in
Rangoon port. Government offices were empty, and the six state-run
daily newspapers did not publish.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PRISON RIOTING _ State-run Radio Rangoon reported 2,000 inmates
set fires at at Insein Jail outside Rangoon and some were shot; 100
prisoners escaped from a prison at Bassein, fires were set and one
inmate was killed by guards; at Akyab jail in Arrakan state, six
inmates were killed, 24 wounded and about 1,600 escaped.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. quoted what it called reliable
sources as saying guards shot and killed about 1,000 inmates during
a riot at Insein Jail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OTHER ACTIVITY _ Rangoon protesters commandeered 27 buses, stole
gasoline and drove the buses around the city. Looting and vandalism
was reported in several townships, and shanties on the outskirts of
the capital were set afire.
   Gen. Tin Oo, a former defense minister, said in a letter to
President Maung Maung that ``the country is in the grip of a
general strike paralyzing the whole administration'' and that it is
imperative to transfer power to an interim government.
</TEXT>
