<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O-Rings     08-27 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O-Rings,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sabotaged O-Rings Not Installed in Shuttle, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Damaged O-rings destined for space shuttle
rockets were apparently sabotaged, but they were caught before they
could be installed in boosters, officials said as NASA and the FBI
investigated.
   However, a former Morton Thiokol employee told a television
station Friday that a deliberately cut O-ring was put in a rocket
segment being assembled at the booster maker's northern Utah plant.
   The 1986 Challenger disaster was blamed on a faulty O-ring that
allowed superhot exhaust gases to escape through a booster joint,
igniting the shuttle's external fuel tank and killing the
seven-member crew.
   A ``very small number'' of O-rings that appeared to have been
deliberately cut were discovered in June, said HydraPak Inc. Vice
President James Dockstader, whose company makes the rings under
contract to Morton Thiokol.
   The discovery was immediately reported to the FBI, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, and Morton Thiokol,
Dockstader said Friday.
   The FBI is investigating the possibility of sabotage, said agent
Cal Clegg, who declined to elaborate.
   NASA Inspector General Bill Colvin likewise refused to discuss
his agency's probe, but said NASA officials believed none of the
damaged O-rings ever reached Morton Thiokol and that their
discovery would not affect plans to launch shuttle Discovery.
   The nation's first shuttle mission since the Challenger tragedy
is expected to be scheduled for late next month or early October.
   Dockstader said a check determined none of the flawed seals was
shipped from HydraPak's plant in suburban West Jordan to Morton
Thiokol, Dockstader said.
   ``The damaged O-rings were immediately secured,'' Dockstader
said. ``No O-rings have been shipped from HydraPak with any kind of
damage.
   ``HydraPak has taken steps to prevent similar incidents in the
future and is confident the problem is now resolved,'' he added.
   NASA spokesman Dwayne Brown said ``extensive inspection and
quality control procedures'' found the damage before the O-rings
left HydraPak's plant.
   But a former Morton Thiokol employee told television station
KTVX he saw a flawed O-ring placed in a rocket segment.
   ``I was there when they received the damaged O-ring, and it was
labeled from HydraPak, and it was in a package that had gone
through quality assurance at Morton Thiokol,'' said the worker, who
was not identified.
   The man said that when he called attention to the flawed seal he
was told to keep quiet because the exposure could cause further
delays in the space shuttle program.
   Morton Thiokol spokesman Rocky Raab denied the allegations.
   ``No unacceptable component has either been delivered to us or
been delivered by us for use in the shuttle program,'' Raab said.
   He said the company conducts extensive inspections of shuttle
parts. Inspection records show there was ``virtually no possibility
that any damaged O-ring has ever gotten into the flight hardware,''
Raab said.
   J.R. Thompson, director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center
in Huntsville, Ala., said some HydraPak employees were suspected of
damaging O-rings to win cash bonuses awarded to workers who found
defects.
   Dockstader denied such an incentive program existed, saying
Thompson was ``either misinformed or misquoted.''
   Former HydraPak inspector Cathy Crocker said she discovered
three O-rings with slash marks as early as May, but management was
unable to determine who was responsible.
   After more cuts were found, Crocker said she was asked to take a
lie-detector test, and agreed because she had ``nothing to hide.''
   ``I took the test and I failed it,'' she told KSL-TV.
   She said that when cuts continued to surface in some O-rings,
she was moved to a filing job and asked to resign.
   Dockstader said no employees were fired because of the
investigations, but wouldn't say whether any were disciplined.
   He said security at HydraPak's plant was strict, including
employee badges for admission and escorts for visitors.
   But Crocker said security was lax and that anyone could walk
into the plant.
</TEXT>
