<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GeographicAction     08-27 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Geographic Action,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Geography Now A Required Course At University Of Colorado</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a University of Colorado student
asked, ``Is New England a separate country?'' action was taken to
make sure the astonishing question wouldn't burn the ears of
faculty again.
   The college has a new requirement for beginning arts and
sciences students of all majors: a geography course.
   ``There had been some deterioration in what we used to think of
as `basic knowledge,''' said Ron James, editor of the Colorado
Alumnus newspaper.
   Bonnie Mahler, an assistant in the School of Arts and Sciences,
said the push to include a geography requirement has won wide
support because the subject is relevant to many disciplines.
   The mandate is part of a larger curriculum reform being
implemented, officials said.
   In most cases, students have a number of options to meet
requirements, but in geography, there are just two choices _ human
geography or international geography.
   Both are designed to give students a ``geographical
perspective'' during the first or second semester.
   Students who can demonstrate a competence in geography on an
entrance exam or who took a similar course in high school are
excused, but officials say most students will have to take one of
the courses.
</TEXT>
