<1ST_LINE>r i PM-IncaFire     08-27 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inca Fire,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Near Inca Ruins In Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fires near the famous Inca ruins of Machu
Picchu have charred at least 15,000 acres, burning trees and
grasslands in several mountain valleys near Cuzco, authorities say.
   But firefighting specialist Wayne Langlois said the fires, many
of them burning since early this month, were not endangering any
ancient sites, including the mountaintop tourist attraction of
Machu Picchu, 40 miles northwest of Cuzco.
   Langlois, of the British Columbia Forest Service in Canada, and
three anti-fire technicians arrived in Peru last week to advise
local officials how to combat the recurring blazes.
   Five hundred soldiers and civilians battling the fires have been
hampered by remote terrain and a shortage of modern equipment such
as chemicals and aircraft, Civil Defense authorities said Friday.
   Langlois said he flew over the burning areas but saw no damage
to farms or any of the stone buildings, bridges, terraced fields
and other ruins of the pre-Hispanic cultures that dot the Cuzco
region.
   Langlois said he believed peasants burning off tough grass for
planting, a traditional practice in the Andes, were accidentally
sparking new fires. Civil Defense authorities say the blazes have
spread because of the extremely dry conditions this year in the
Peruvian highlands.
</TEXT>
