<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NIreland-IRA     08-27 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-IRA,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode In Northern Ireland Cities After Extradition Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four bombs exploded early today
outside Belfast City Hall, in a nearby shopping complex and in
Londonderry following the extradition of a convicted guerrilla
leader from the Republic of Ireland to this British province,
police said.
   There were no reports of casualties in Belfast, but one
policeman suffered minor injuries in Londonderry when a bomb
exploded in a car left on a bridge, police said. Officials said the
injured policemen was trying to evacuate the area after authorities
had received a telephoned warning.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bombs, which went off
hours after guerrilla chieftain Robert Russell was extradited to
Northern Ireland to resume a 20-year prison sentence for the
attempted murder of a police officer.
   Earlier in the night, hundreds of IRA supporters clashed with
police outside Dublin's Mountjoy prison as security forces prepared
to transport Russell 50 miles to the border, police said.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army is fighting to end British
rule in Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite the
province with the Irish Republic, which is predominantly Roman
Catholic.
   Russell, 30, is charged in connection with his escape from
prison in 1983. A last legal bid to stop his extradition failed in
the High Court in Dublin on Friday.
   In a series of complicated manuevers, police said they drove to
a secretly arranged spot near the border where Russell was handed
over to Northern Ireland police, put in a helicopter and flown 30
miles to Lisburn near Belfast.
   About 400 demonstrators massed near the border began attacking
police with fists, stones and bottles. Chief Superintendent John
Nolan of the Garda Siochana, or Irish Republic police, said three
of his men were hurt in the fighting.
   Russell escaped from Northern Ireland's Maze Prison in a mass
breakout by IRA inmates in September 1983. He fled to the Republic
of Ireland, was arrested in Dublin in 1984 and began a complicated
series of legal maneuvers in a bid to avoid being extradited back
to Northern Ireland.
   He had argued that the attempted murder for which he was
convicted in Northern Ireland was a political act and that
therefore he was a political fugitive and could not be convicted.
   But the Republic of Ireland last year agreed a new extradition
treaty with Britain under which this defense is no longer valid.
   The IRA has killed 27 British military personnel this year and
has launched a summer campaign of bombings and assassinations in
Northern Ireland, mainland Britain and Europe. It announced
Wednesday a new strategy for bombing ``commercial and
administrative property'' at minimal risk to civilians.
</TEXT>
