<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bonefish     08-27 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonefish,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Investigators Say Cost Too High To Repair Damaged Sub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy investigators have recommended
scrapping the fire-damaged submarine USS Bonefish because it would
cost more than $100 million to repair, a newspaper reported
Saturday.
   Three sailors were killed and 23 injured in April when the
diesel-powered vessel caught fire off the Florida coast.
   A report to Adm. Frank B. Kelso, commander of the Norfolk-based
Atlantic Fleet, suggests scrapping the 30-year-old sub but does not
suggest how to do it.
   ``There is no easy way to put the Bonefish back into commission.
It was very badly damaged,'' a Navy officer familiar with the
investigation and the report told The Virginian-Pilot and The
Ledger-Star.
   Navy officials said it would be inappropriate to comment on the
report, which has not been made public, until all reviews have been
completed.
   After Kelso completes his review, the report will be forwarded
to the Navy's judge advocate general and the chief of naval
operations.
   The investigators said the fire was caused by a wet battery
cable that short-circuited, and not by a buildup of hydrogen gas as
originally thought, the newspaper reported in Saturday's editions.
   The Bonefish was one of the Navy's four diesel-electric attack
subs, all built in the 1950s and all to be decommissioned by the
end of this decade.
</TEXT>
