<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0419 08-27 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0419,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs with Dukakis in Washington, comments from
speech, pickup graf 3rd pvs, bgng, ``The Massachusetts .....
^By JOHN KING</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today joined tens of thousands
commemorating the march on Washington by 25 years ago by Martin
Luther King Jr. and paid tribute to the slain civil rights leader
who ``even in death ... has the power to look down upon us and see
into our souls.''
   The Democratic presidential nominee flew to the nation's capital
this morning to participate in the march from the Washington
monument to the Lincoln Memorial.
   In a speech he was to deliver there this afternoon, Dukakis
likened King to Lincoln and promised if elected president to work
to fulfill the ``dream'' King spoke of at the end of the 1963 march.
   ``What is it about a man that eve though most of us did not know
him, we felt as if we did,'' Dukakis said in the text of his
speech, released in advance.
   ``And although he did not knowmost of us, we feel that even in
death he has the power to look down upon us and see into our souls.
   ``Like the man whose memorial we gather at today, Martin Luther
King was such a man,'' Dukakis said. ``And as Abraham Lincoln, in
his time, defined our nation's purpose at Gettysburg; so Dr. King,
in his time, defined America's soul.''
   Dukakis said blacks and other minorities have made great strides
in the quarter century since the march but, quoting John F.
Kennedy, said further work lies ahead. ``This is the side of the
hill, not the top,'' Dukakis said in quoting the late president.
   Dukakis paid tribute to former rival Jesse Jackson, also at the
march, as someone ``Dr. King must be very proud of;'' and applauded
Republican challenger George Bush for his support of
antidiscrimination laws to protect AIDS victims.
   But he rattled off a list of issues on which he implied the
Reagan administration has failed to help minorities and said the
war on racism would not be won ``until we have a president who
understands and respects the Constitution of the United States.''
   From Washington, Dukakis was headed to western Massachusetts to
spend the weekend with his wife at her father's cottage.
   The Massachusetts governor spent all day Friday catching up on
state business and attended a fund-raiser for state Sen. Royal
Bolling Sr. before heading home for the evening. Bolling, the
state's only black senator, is a longtime friend of the governor's
and served with him in the House in the 1960s.
   It was during a short walk from the Statehouse to the historic
African Meeting House, the site of the Bolling event, that Dukakis
spoke about King and his march on Washington.
   ``It was one of the great historic events in the history of this
country and it came at a time when black people and minority
citizens were facing terrible discrimination,'' Dukakis said. ``It
was an historic event which triggered a civil rights revolution in
this country.''
   There was an awkward moment at the fund-raiser as Dukakis was
introduced by the senator's son, Boston City Councilor Bruce
Bolling, who was co-chairman of Jackson's Massachusetts campaign
and recently criticized Dukakis for not bringing more Jackson
followers into his campaign.
   Bruce Bolling discussed his support of Jackson but then praised
Dukakis' record as a legislator and governor on issues of concern
to minorities and for his plans to attend the march.
   ``That sign alone means so much substantively and symbolically
of where we need to go in this country,'' the younger Bolling said.
``Michael Dukakis will be there. George Bush will not.''
   Aides to Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, said the
vice president cannot attend because of a scheduling conflict.
   Dukakis did not mention Bush at the fund-raiser but had kind
words for his rival earlier in the day when asked about the vice
president's statement that deployment of the costly ``Star Wars''
space defense program should be contingent on further research.
   ``I think that makes sense,'' Dukakis said of Bush's stance.
``I'm glad to see that the vice president now agrees with me and a
great number of American citizens.''
   It was a rare Friday at the Statehouse for Dukakis, who for
months has left the state by midweek to campaign. In recent weeks,
he has spent two or three days in Boston but will cut the time he
spends at home in half after Labor Day, spokesman Dayton Duncan
said.
   ``He'll be campaigning increasingly in the fall, around five
days a week,'' Duncan said. ``It will mean a day less at the
Statehouse.''
</TEXT>
