<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     08-27 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says Officials Agreed To Wait Till 1989 To Charge Marcos And Allow
Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil and military authorities agreed
secretly two months ago to wait until at least next year before
filing charges against Ferdinand Marcos and allowing the ousted
president to return, a former official said Saturday.
   Ramon Diaz, who resigned this month as chairman of the
Presidential Commission on Good Government, told The Associated
Press that he reached the agreement on the timetable with military
Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa before President Corazon Aquino
visited Switzerland last June.
   Diaz said he sought de Villa's advice on the possibility of
Marcos returning after the government gave up hope that the U.S.
government would allow a Filipino court to try the deposed
president on American soil.
   He said de Villa asked for ``a little more time to make sure of
the stability of the situation.'' Diaz qouted de Villa as saying
the first three months of 1989 would be ``a fairly reasonable
time'' to prepare for Marcos coming home.
   ``We will have to consult with the (military) because,
naturally, they will be the ones who will bear the brunt if any
problems arise,'' Diaz added.
   As chairman of the good government commission, Diaz was the
principal official responsible for tracking down the estimated $10
billion that Filipino authorities say Marcos embezzled during his
20-year administration.
   Much of the money was believed to have been stashed in secret
Swiss bank accounts. Swiss authorities have refused to lift banking
secrecy laws until the government files criminal charges against
Marcos.
   But Philippine law bans trials in absentia, and the government
has delayed criminal proceedings for fear Marcos would insist on
attending the trial.
   Last year, Filipino authorities privately asked American
officials about the possibility of trying Marcos in Hawaii, where
he has lived since the February 1986 uprising that toppled his
administration and swept Mrs. Aquino into the presidency.
   U.S. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
told the Filipinos they disapproved of the plan for various
constitutional and procedural reasons.
   Last Wednesday, Marcos filed a petition with the anti-corruption
court asking permission to return home when a former Cabinet
minister gives a deposition on alleged kickbacks by Japanese firms
during the previous administration.
   But Mrs. Aquino ordered Solicitor-General Francisco Chavez to
ask the court to reject Marcos' petition. Chavez said he would
appeal to the Supreme Court if the lower tribunal rules in favor of
Marcos.
   The anti-corruption court has ruled that Marcos would be within
his rights to ask to be present when former public works minister
Baltazar Aquino gives his deposition in November.
   The court stopped short of ordering Marcos to return for the
deposition hearing. Former minister Aquino is no relation to the
president.
   Diaz said Chavez violated the agreement with the military on the
timetable for charges by asking the court to schedule the
deposition hearing in November.
   In Hawaii, Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad withheld comment on
the government's plans to block the former president's return
because ``we are confused by all the reports'' on the proceedings.
   ``Mrs. Aquino has said that the country is very stable and she's
not worried about any Marcos return,'' Trinidad told Manila radio
station DZXL in a telephone interview from Honolulu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
