<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle-Media     08-27 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Media,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two-Thirds Say National Guard Story Overblown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of Americans believe news coverage
of the troubles of Republican vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle
has been unfair, according to a poll released Saturday by Times
Mirror corporation.
   The survey conducted by the Gallup Organization said 55 percent
of people questioned said they thought coverage of the Indiana
senator was unfair. Thirty-nine percent called the coverage fair.
   In addition, 69 percent of the respondents said the story had
received too much coverage, while only 2 percent said it had been
given too little.
   The survey of 1,000 likely voters was conducted Wednesday and
Thursday and had a margin of error of 3 percent.
   The poll was part of the Los Angeles based media company's
series, ``The People, The Press & Politics,'' which has tried to
measure public attitudes toward the news media.
   While people surveyed were critical of coverage of the Quayle
story, they also gave him far lower ratings than his Democratic
counterpart, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, when asked if they were
qualified to serve as president.
   When asked, ``Based on what you know about the Republican vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle, do you think he is qualified to
serve as president?'' 41 percent said yes, and 40 percent said he
was not.
   When the same question was asked about Bentsen, 62 percent said
yes and 16 percent said no.
   On Quayle's National Guard service, only 15 percent said they
had a less favorable opinion of him because he served in the Guard
during the Vietnam War, while 82 percent said that did not lower
their opinion of him.
   While people said they thought the news media had overplayed the
story and been unfair, 56 percent also answered in the affirmative
when asked if they thought ``it is important that voters learn
about the details of Dan Quayle's past in order to judge whether he
would be a good vice president.'' A total of 38 percent said they
did not think information about his past was relevant to
determining his ability to serve as vice president.
   The survey also showed a steady decline in Bush's unfavorable
ratings.
   On the current poll, 30 percent of people said they had
unfavorable opinions of Bush. A Gallup survey a week earlier had
him getting a negative rating from 33 percent, while a month
earlier it was 40 percent and in May, 44 percent.
   When asked about Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis, 33 percent said they had an unfavorable opinion, virtually
the same figure as in the previous two surveys. Last May, Dukakis'
unfavorable rating was 22 percent.
</TEXT>
