<DOCNO> AP880827-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AdmiralDisciplined     08-27 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Admiral Disciplined,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral Asks To Retire After Being Disciplined For Personal
Misconduct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the Navy's highest-ranking admirals has
asked to retire after being disciplined for alleged personal
misconduct while stationed in Italy, according to the Navy and
defense sources.
   Vice Adm. Kendall E. Moranville, until Aug. 20 the commander of
the Navy's 6th Fleet, ``was taken to admiral's mast'' on Aug. 19,
said Capt. Brent Baker, a Navy spokesman.
   ``Vice Adm. Moranville was given a punitive letter of reprimand
at admiral's mast,'' Baker said. ``The action taken at the
admiral's mast is presently under review. ... Vice Adm. Moranville
has requested retirement.''
   Baker, noting that the results of the disciplinary hearing were
being reviewed by Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, chief of naval
operations, refused to discuss the nature of the alleged misconduct
beyond saying it involved ``several alleged improprieties.''
   Asked about statements by other defense sources that the
allegations included adultery, Baker would only say the allegations
``had no connection with Vice Adm. Moranville's operational
responsibilities as commander, 6th Fleet.''
   ``In fact, he continued to do an outstanding job as commander,
6th Fleet, until relieved on Aug. 20,'' Baker said. ``But in
recognition of Vice Adm. Moranville's rights in the matter, it
would be inappropriate to discuss the matter further.''
   Baker said Moranville was traveling to Washington on Friday ``on
temporary assignment pending review of his admiral's mast.'' The
spokesman declined to attempt to contact him for comment.
   The Navy's 6th Fleet is headquartered in Naples, Italy.
   The 56-year-old Moranville was replaced as the 6th Fleet
commander on Aug. 20 in a routine, long-scheduled rotation. What
was not routine, however, was that Moranville departed his old post
without the Navy announcing new orders for him.
   The Navy rarely proceeds with a change of command involving
officers at the rank of three stars without having announced the
next job of the officer who is moving on.
   In this case, the sources said Moranville, a veteran pilot who
fought in Vietnam, had been widely rumored to be on his way back to
Washington after serving two years as the head of the Navy fleet
that operates in the Mediterranean Sea.
   According to one Navy source, Moranville was thought to be
returning to the Pentagon to become the next deputy chief of naval
operations for naval warfare.
   The Navy announced last May 18 the current deputy chief for
naval warfare, Vice Adm. James R. Hogg, had been tapped to become
the next U.S. representative to the NATO Military Committee. The
service still has not announced Hogg's successor.
   Although Moranville has now requested retirement, the review of
the punishment meted out at the admiral's mast could still be
important. As is the case with any flag officer of three- or
four-star rank, it is up to the chief of naval operations and the
Navy's secretary to decide whether to recommend retirement at the
grade an officer currently holds.
   It is then up to the Senate to make the final decision.
   Moranville won the three-star rank of vice admiral on June 1,
1985.
   An admiral's mast is a closed-door, non-judicial proceeding
during which an admiral reviews the evidence and decides if any
discipline is warranted.
   In this case, Baker said Moranville had appeared at mast on Aug.
19 before Adm. James B. Busey, the commander-in-chief of U.S. Naval
Forces Europe.
   Baker said the allegations against Moranville did not ``come to
light'' until shortly before the vice admiral already had been
scheduled for routine rotation.
   Moranville, a native of Guide Rock, Neb., is a highly decorated
aviator who holds two Legion of Merit medals, the Air Medal with
Numeral ``10,'' and two Navy Commendation Medal with Combat ``V.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
