<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Catnapping     08-27 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catnapping,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Crack Catnapping Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It could go in the books as a
cat-and-mouse caper.
   When Amy DeDonatis reported her cat, Marilyn, was being held for
$3,200 ransom, police began plotting the trap.
   ``We set it up like we would have any other extortion operation.
With the highest concern for the ... cat's safety,'' said police
Sgt. Bob Robkin.
   The 2-year-old white cat was snatched on Aug. 14 by a man
claiming Ms. DeDonatis owed his girlfriend $3,200, the cost to
repair the woman's Porsche after a recent accident that occurred
while Ms. DeDonatis was driving the car.
   ``He said, `Are you going to give us the money?' And I said,
`Not until I see the cat,' '' Ms. DeDonatis recalled.
   Police gave Ms. DeDonatis ``flash money'' and staked out the
site Thursday where the ransom drop had been arranged, an alley
behind the salon where she works as a hairdresser.
   Soon a man showed up, with Marilyn in tow.
   ``I was so happy I just handed him the money,'' Ms. DeDonatis
said.
   That's when police moved in. They arrested Eddie Perez-Pantoja,
30, on charges of grand theft and extortion.
   Marilyn was taken to headquarters and photographed as evidence,
then released. Once home, she had little appetite _ and just took a
catnap.
   ``She looked a little freaked out,'' her owner said.
</TEXT>
