<1ST_LINE>u w PM-MarchonWashington 2ndLd-Writethru a0456 08-27 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-March on Washington, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0456,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally to Press King's Civil Rights Demands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with rally speeches, Reagan statement; picks
up pvs 3rd graf bgng, Jackson.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of civil rights demonstrators
chanting ``Keep Hope Alive'' rallied today for the 25th anniversary
of the Martin Luther King's March on Washington and renewed his
demands for peace, jobs and freedom.
   The crowd at the foot of the Washington Monument was far smaller
than the quarter-million marchers who jammed the National Mall to
hear King's famous ``I Have a Dream'' speech in 1963.
   The U.S. Park Police made an early estimate of 20,000
demonstrators today, but the throng was expected to grow by the
time Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and civil rights leader
Jesse Jackson deliver their speeches in late afternoon.
   President Reagan, who spent the day campaigning for Republican
candidates in California, issued a statement saying America ``has
made vast progress toward fully achieving Dr. King's dream of a
color-blind society.''
   As a result, Reagan said, ``America today is a freer land for
Americans of all backgrounds.'' He added that ``freedom is our
unending challenge and our continuing vocation as Americans.''
   But at the rally, one speaker after another said King's dream of
equality is far from being realized.
   ``We are here looking for jobs, looking for peace and looking
for freedom,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.
   ``There are some who will say that freedom is reciting the
Pledge of Allegiance, but that is not what we mean when we say
freedom,'' Rangel added. ``Freedom means our children can get an
education as easily as they can get cocaine in our schools.''
   Jackson appeared briefly and led the rally in his trademark
chant of ``Keep Hope Alive!''
   On the eve of the march, Jackson told a cheering crowd of black
activists that Dukakis, his former rival for the Democratic
nomination, and running mate Lloyd Bentsen provide ``a choice and a
chance in November ... an alternative, a chance to change.''
   Jackson, Dukakis and Coretta Scott King, widow of the slain
civil rights leader, were to address the rally today.
   An estimated 250,000 people marched in Washington on Aug. 28,
1963.The same number of people commemorated the 20th anniversary of
the march five years ago.
   During the 1963 event, the largest demonstration in history in
the nation's capital, Martin Luther King outlined his vision of a
color-blind America where all citizens had equal economic,
political and social opportunity. The march spurred Congress to
pass the landmark Civil Rights Act of 1964.
   Jackson lashed out Friday at the Republican ticket of Vice
President George Bush and Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana.
   ``Bush and Quayle want to privatize the Justice Department. They
want to privatize foreign policy. They want to privatize public
education,'' said Jackson.
   ``And since they like privacy so much, I want to help them move
back into private life,'' Jackson told a lunch meeting of the A.
Philip Randolph Institute, an organization of trade unionists named
after the late black labor leader.
   Neither Bush nor Quayle had responded to an invitation to join
the commemoration, said Ofield Dukes, a spokesman for the march
organizers.
   A Bush spokesman said the GOP presidential nominee would be
campaigning in Texas today.
   The tide of rhetoric was running against the Republicans in
advance of the march.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland, addressing the same lunch
audience as Jackson, said, ``It was black voters, more than any
other factor, that held the line against Reaganism four years ago
and turned the tide against it two years ago.''
   ``The decisions made by black voters will be no less crucial
this time around,'' said Kirkland, whose labor federation voted
Wednesday to endorse Dukakis and Bentsen.
   ``The plagues of Egypt lasted seven years. The Reagan
administration has been allotted one more year than that,''
Kirkland said. ``The job before us is to see that the curse is
lifted from the land on schedule, and that the incumbent and his
chosen successor get their termination notice on Election Day.
   ``That will give them 72 days to pack up and clear out, which is
generous. They themselves believe that workers deserve no notice at
all,'' said Kirkland, alluding to a new law opposed by Reagan that
requires employers to give workers 60 days' notice of large-scale
layoffs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
