<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AcidRainLobbying     08-27 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Acid Rain Lobbying,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lobbying Group Spending Millions to Combat Acid Rain Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utilities, coal producers and other businesses
have poured $6.5 million into a lobbying organization whose goal is
to stifle congressional legislation that would reduce acid rain, a
public interest group said Saturday.
   Citizens for Sensible Control of Acid Rain has received its
contributions exclusively from industry ever since its founding in
1983, according to figures compiled by the U.S. Public Interest
Research Group. The lobbyists have spent $5.1 million so far,
including $500,000 from April to June of this year, the group said.
   ``Few people realize that their power company may be bankrolling
an effort to block clean air legislation while contributing
enormously to our air pollution problems,'' said Alexandra Allen, a
staff attorney for the group.
   The figures, obtained from the clerk of the House, indicate that
most of the money _ $4.3 million _ has gone to Communications
Management Inc. of Arlington, Va., for legislative consulting and
public relations.
   The biggest contributor has been Southern Company Services Inc.
of Atlanta, which has donated $2.3 million to the organization. The
lobbyists reported receipts from 114 companies, the report said.
</TEXT>
