<DOCNO> AP880827-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfTalks Bjt   08-27 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks, Bjt,0906</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Still Separated By Centuries Of Hostility</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beneath 40-year-old murals depicting the end of
wars and plagues, the envoys of warring Iran and Iraq entered the
grand chamber separately and skeptically to sit at opposite tables
for peace talks.
   They faced each other across a gulf of gray carpeting 15 feet
wide and a another gulf of centuries-old hatred. They called each
other ``monsieur,'' ``excellency,'' and ``colleague,'' but after
two days of direct and separate talks under U.N. auspices both
sides remained far apart.
   Ater eight years of the war and more than a thousand years of
Arab-Persian enmity, no one expected the long peace process to be
without pitfalls or its first step in Geneva to be easy.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar recessed the talks
Saturday for a ``day of reflection'' after both sides set out their
divergent positions on numerous, contentious issues, from the
Shatt-Al-Arab waterway dispute to the repatriation of more than
80,000 prisoners of war.
   The talks are to resume Sunday.
   ``We are working, I must admit, at a rather slow pace ... in an
atmosphere of mistrust,'' Perez de Cuellar told reporters Saturday.
``So far, the talks have been highly polite and they have listened
to each other with patience and, I hope, understanding.''
   But while the week-old gulf cease-fire continued, Iraq was
continuing poison gas attacks against its own rebellious Kurdish
minority, killing 200 and injuring 1,000 in the last few days,
Kurdish guerrilla leaders told the Associated Press in Nicosia.
   The Security Council in New York, meanwhile, denounced the
repeated use of chemical warfare against Iran. U.N. experts have
said Iraq has ignored U.N. appeals against using the morally
repugnant weapons banned under international law.
   On Friday night, after the talks were suspended, the U.N. chief
said: ``It is too early to ask for flexibility. I hope that after
reflection, perhaps flexibility will start later.''
   Their two days of peace talks, which began Thursday, were the
first face-to-face discussions between the envoys since the gulf
war began eight years ago in September 1980.
   The talks are aimed at consolidating a fragile week-old gulf
cease-fire and moving toward a comprehensive peace settlement. The
secretary-general said the talks could drag on for years, if
problems persist, or could lead to a settlement in a few months if
both parties show the political will.
   The Iraqi side has not commented, but Iranian President Ali
Khamenei on Saturday accused Iraq of procrastination and ``trying
to degrade the role of the secretary-general and the U.N. peace
resolution.''
   ``If Iraq continues its way,'' he said, ``talks may go on for
years and may never come to a conclusion.'' His comments to
journalists were reported on Tehran Radio and monitored in Nicosia.
   After two days of talks both in the same room and in separate
chambers, inevitable problems became evident, especially over the
Shatt-Al-Arab waterway. It is the disputed border between Iran and
Iraq and the only outlet to the sea for landlocked Iraq.
   Western and Middle Eastern diplomats said Iraq, which had scored
a series of impressive military victories, was taking a hard and
uncompromising position in the talks and seeking to make the
waterway dispute a high priority on the agenda.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Iran,
badly battered in the war, was taking a more cooperative position,
but it, too, was unyielding on key issues.
   Iran says the waterway and other issues are not on the agenda.
Iraq says that the waterway and other problems must be discussed at
this time.
   The diplomats also said the Iraqi side, which demanded
face-to-face talks, appeared to be annoyed and to feel it was being
rushed and pressured into accepting a timetable before its
suspicions about Iranian intentions were allayed.
   On July 18, after resisting the U.N. peace resolution 598 for
one year, the war-weary Tehran government abruptly announced it
would accept a U.N.-monitored cease-fire and pushed for an
immediate end to hostilities.
   Then it was Iraq, which had formally embraced the resolution for
a year, that held back and demanded face-to-face talks before a
cease-fire. Iraq said it feared Iran merely was seeking a temporary
truce to rebuild its forces before continuing the war. It said
early talks were necessary to test Iran's good intentions.
   Iran refused. Both sides compromised on talks shortly after the
cease-fire, which began Aug. 20.
   On Friday, Velayati broke his silence on the talks and said Iran
insists that the 1975 Algiers Treaty, which gives Tehran rights to
the eastern half of the the Shatt-Al-Arab, is valid. He said
observing the treaty, unilaterally repudiated by Iraq before it
invaded in 1980, is a fundamental condition for peace.
   The secretary-general has said that points have been clarified
in the current discussions and that both sides appear sincere in
their desire for peace.
   ``But this is a problem that has lasted many centuries,'' he
said, ``and it is not in one afternoon that we can decide it.''
   Iran's culture is Persian, and Iraq's is Arab. Although Iran
shares the Moslem religion with the Arabs, it adheres to the
minority Shiite sect that has been at odds with the predominant
Sunni branch of Islam for 1,300 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880827-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PrisonFines     08-27 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Fines,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DC Ordered To Pay $1.3 Million In Fines Due To Prison Overcrowding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has ordered the
District of Columbia to pay $1.3 million in fines because of its
failure to alleviate crowded conditions at the city-run Lorton
Reformatory in Fairfax County, Va.
   ``The district has for years been aware of recurrent
overcrowding in its prison, and has not taken steps adequate to
eradicate the problem,'' the court stated in its decision Friday.
The judges also faulted the city for failing to build a ``sorely
needed new prison facility'' or to find other solutions.
   The fines were originally imposed by a U.S. District Court judge
last year, and have been increasing at a rate of about $5,000 per
day since then. The city immediately challenged the fines and
refused to pay anything until its appeal was ruled upon.
   On Friday, the appeals panel decided the city was out of time.
   ``It is our hope that, confronted by the prospect of heavy
fines, the district will at last face up to its responsibilities,''
Judge Spottswood W. Robinson III wrote for the court.
   He added that ``the limits of judicial tolerance have been
reached.''
   City officials were not expected to appeal the ruling. D.C.
Corrections Director Hallem Williams Jr. said through a spokesman
he was ``disappointed in the court's ruling.''
   ``It's going to be very expensive'' for the city to continue
exceeding the population ceiling at Lorton, said Alan Pemberton, an
attorney for the inmates at the Central Facility at Lorton.
   The city has been given a population limit of 1,125 inmates at
Lorton's medium-security Central Facility, which is currently
housing about 400 extra prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
