<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen     08-27 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brands Bush With ``Outrageous Misrepresentation'' On Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen on Saturday charged Vice President George Bush with
``an outrageous misrepresentation of the facts'' for accusing
Michael Dukakis of failing to fight drug use.
   Bentsen, wrapping up a five-day campaign swing with a stop in
his native Texas, visited the local sheriffs department and then
met with reporters to counter the Republican accusations.
   ``George Bush comes to Texas, goes to Longview, and charges Mike
Dukakis with being soft on the war on drugs,'' said Bentsen. ``That
is an outrageous misrepresentation of the facts.''
   In Massachusetts, Bentsen said, the homicide rate is half the
national average, Dukakis has added 1,500 law enforcement
personnel, and pushed programs to help victims of crime.
   ``I don't think (Dukakis' record) has been surpassed by any
other state in the nation,'' he said.
   Bentsen, who added the Texas stop to his schedule to counter
Bush's campaigning in the state that both call home, said the vice
president himself has failed to stop drugs despite being appointed
head of a drug interdiction task force by President Reagan.
   ``This administration has rhetoric that isn't balanced by the
realities,'' Bentsen said, citing attempts by the White House to
cut back what Congress planned to spend on drugs, particularly $225
million in aid that was earmarked for local law enforcement.
   ``They've been talking tough and cutting back the money at the
same time,'' he said.
   Asked about the death penalty, Bentsen said he supports it but
Dukakis continues to oppose it. And he conceded that he and Dukakis
have differences over gun control also _ although he said Dukakis
does believe in the ultimate right of people to own guns to protect
their homes or hunt.
   ``I think what you have to look (at) ... is beyond some of the
symbols,'' of tough law enforcement, and look at the results, he
said.
   Much of Bentsen's campaign trip was spent in the Midwest and
South, trying to sell Democrats who voted for Reagan on the
Massachusetts governor and his positions on national defense,
trade, health care, and law enforcement.
   Bentsen told reporters on his campaign plane that he felt he was
making progress in convincing people Dukakis is their man.
   ``I still think we have to work at making it understood on the
defense issues,'' he said. ``But I think we'll get our message
across.''
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., who met with Bentsen in Hot Springs
where the senator received a raucus, enthusiastic welcome on
Friday, said the Texas senator was an important element in the
party's efforts to win back Reagan Democrats.
   ``Bentsen allows the middle class, white, middle age,
independent businessman to feel comfortable with the Democratic
ticket,'' he said. ``He gives a lot of them a reason to come back.''
   Bentsen said he gauged his success at the large number of local
elected officials who wanted to appear with him when he travels in
the South. ``There's not room enough on the dais,'' he said.
</TEXT>
