<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LastTemptation     08-27 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vandals Delay Utah Opening Of ``Last Temptation Of Christ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late-night vandals briefly delayed the
Utah premier of the ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' by unrolling
the film from its reel and slashing the movie screen, authorities
say.
   Police Detective Lt. Mel Shields said the theater canceled only
its 1 p.m. showing Friday of the movie that has drawn the wrath of
some religious groups, because of its depiction of Christ. It
obtained another copy of the film and fixed the screen in time for
the 4 p.m. show.
   Lt. Steve Diamond said the film was originally thought to have
been stolen, but it was found later in the basement.
   ``They (vandals) took it there and dumped it in a big pile, as
it were,'' he said. ``It was dumped off the spool. We now have it
in our evidence room.''
   When the theater finally opened, police officers inside searched
handbags for sharp objects or projectiles.
   One police officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the vandals probably remained in the building after Thursday
night's shows. He said a rear exit appeared to have been opened
from the inside.
   Inside, police found 5-foot-long slashes on the screen.
   Shields said police had no suspects.
   Earlier, police had issued a demonstration permit to a Utah
religious group opposed to the movie, which has been condemned by
the Mormon Church, predominant in the state.
</TEXT>
