<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 5thLd-Writethru   08-27 0932</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0549,a0560,0959</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>36 Prisoners Reported Killed In Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT time element, Friday sted
today, and ADD report of 500 prisoners escaping. Pickup 4th pvs,
`By today...'
^By SEIN WIN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guards shot to death 36 prisoners and
wounded 103 others who tried to escape from a Rangoon jail in an
escalation of the unrest in Burma, state-run Radio Rangoon said
today.
   More than 500 prisoners also escaped today from a jail in the
southern city of Mergui, 350 miles south of the capital, the radio
said.
   As the law and order situation in Burma deteriorated, a popular
former defense minister and an ailing leader of the communist
movement joined widespread calls for an interim government to end
the country's authoritarian, one-party rule.
   Radio Rangoon said prisoners burned buildings and tried to scale
the walls at Insein Jail, eight miles north of downtown Rangoon, in
their escape bid Friday.
   By today, all the jail buildings had burned to the ground, the
radio reported without saying if the rioting had ended.
   ``So prison personnel had to control the situation and
unavoidably had to shoot,'' the broadcast said. ``As a result, 36
prisoners were killed and 103 injured.''
   Earlier, Radio Rangoon said seven inmates were killed and at
least 1,000 escaped during uprisings at three prisons across the
country. Strikes closed factories, government offices and
transportation.
   Sources said student activists on Friday circulated photographs
of six men they said were caught in acts of arson, bombings and
shootings. The students said the six were identified by their
military units and confessed to being military intelligence
officers who were ordered to create disorder.
   Retired Gen. Tin Oo told a rally of about 50,000 people in
downtown Rangoon that a transitional government must be formed
immediately to end the turmoil that has toppled two leaders,
sparked almost daily demonstrations nationwide and killed at least
112 people.
   ``Following the recent public demonstrations against the
one-party regime, the light of democracy has now been visible,''
Tin Oo said. ``But the final goal has yet to be achieved.''
   ``I therefore urge the government to immediately form an interim
government to ease the situation and allow the interim government
to prepare for democratic reforms,'' he said.
   Tin Oo said the military must play an important role in
re-establishing democracy.
   Tin Oo, 62, widely respected by both the military and the
public, was removed as defense minister and army chief of staff in
1976 by strongman Ne Win. At that time, he was considered the
third-ranking member of the ruling hierarchy and had a strong
following in the military. He was later jailed after an
investigation into an alleged plot against the government.
   He said today he was not interested in political office.
   ``When a multiparty system is eventually introduced, I for one
will not stand for any election. I won't be in politics. I have now
come in simply because the situation has developed into a serious
national matter,'' Tin Oo said.
   Many retired top military officers attended Tin Oo's rally,
along with Buddhist monks and students.
   One of Burma's former communist leaders, Thakin Soe, issued a
statement from his bed in Rangoon General Hospital calling for a
return to multiparty government.
   The statement supported the mass demonstrations for democracy
and demanded the government form an interim government and restore
peace.
   Thakin Soe, 82, formed the pro-Chinese faction of the Communist
Party in 1937. He spent most of his life underground, but was
captured after army suppression campaigns in the late 1960s and
granted amnesty in 1980. His party no longer exists and he is not
active in the movement.
   The situation in Burma has deteriorated since President Maung
Maung lifted martial law Wednesday and security personnel virtually
disappeared from Rangoon's streets.
   On Friday, Radio Rangoon said guards at Insein Jail fired on
2,000 rioting inmates ``and some inmates and prison warders were
injured.'' Sources said there could have been many people killed,
but the situation remained confused and they did not believe even
the government had precise casualty figures.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said the rebellion at Insein Jail
occurred Friday morning and that about 1,000 inmates were killed.
The BBC broadcast, monitored in London, said:
   ``Anti-government demonstrations are reported to have begun .. .
(at Insein Jail) early in the day when prisoners had left their
cells for breakfast. Several who tried to give speeches are said to
have been shot dead and in the chaos that followed, fires were
started.
   ``As inmates fled to escape the flames, it is reported that
security guards opened fire. According to reliable sources, about
1,000 people were killed.''
   The report could not be independently verified.
   Pro-democracy strikes halted all rail service and Union Burma
Airways domestic flights; closed oil refineries in Syriam across
the Rangoon River and in Mann in central Burma; crippled most
factories of the Industries Ministry; and left foreign ships
waiting at Rangoon port, officials said.
   Most government offices in Rangoon were empty. People were
hoarding goods and the price of rice was soaring.
   The current turmoil in Burma began when Ne Win, who led the 1962
coup that ended democracy and instituted rigid socialist rule,
resigned and the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party named
hardliner Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Demonstrations began almost immediately against Sein Lwin,
widely hated for ruthlessly crushing dissent. They turned bloody
Aug. 8 when security forces fired on protesters. Sein Lwin resigned
Aug. 12.
   On Aug. 19, Maung Maung became Burma's first civilian president
in 26 years.
</TEXT>
