<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20 farm group representatives
shook Willie Nelson's hand and gave the country singer a banner to
thank him for calling attention to the plight of family farmers.
   ``It would be hard for you to realize the hope you're giving
farmers,'' Ken Mattingly of the Community Farm Alliance of Kentucky
told Nelson on Friday night.
   He gave Nelson a banner reading ``Thanks for all your help,
Willie.''
   ``You never know how much you can help until you get involved,''
said Nelson, who was in town for a concert.
   Nelson organized Farm Aid, a series of concerts betinning in
1985 to raise money for family farmers facing bankruptcy and the
loss of their land. He plans a fourth Farm Aid concert in
Washington, D.C., in 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former professional football player
J.D. Hill has been ordered to attend a drug treatment program
following his arrest for alleged cocaine possession.
   Hill, 39, who has long campaigned against drugs, was among 27
people arrested July 15 during an undercover operation in which
police posed as sellers of crack cocaine and arrested customers.
   On Friday, Sacramento Municipal Court Judge John V. Stroud
placed Hill on a yearlong drug diversion program and fined him $50.
   Hill was a wide receiver for the Buffalo Bills of the National
Football League from 1971 to 1975, playing in the all-star Pro Bowl
in 1972. He then played for the Detroit Lions before retiring in
1978.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy award-winning American filmaker
Francis Ford Coppola visited the 2,400-year-old Acropolis temple
complex Saturday where he plans to set the last scene of his movie
``Life Without Zoe.''
   The partly autobiographical 40-minute film will form part of a
trilogy called ``New York Stories,'' said Coppola, 49. Directors
Woody Allen and Martin Scorsese are making the other two movies, he
said.
   ``It's a very romantic film and is the story of a little girl,
Zoe _ named after the Greek word for life _ who represents a kind
of irresistible life force in her family. Her father, a flutist, is
based on the character of my own father,'' the director said.
   Coppola said ``the precocious little girl'' is obsessed with the
Acropolis because of its historical associations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Deborah Raffin has received eath
threats, and an actor once managed by her husband is under court
order to stay away from both of them and not harass them, their
lawyer said.
   Santa Monica Superior Court Judge Lawrence Waddington issued a
temporary restraining order Thursday requiring Steven Inwood not to
harass Miss Raffin and her manager-husband, Michael Viner, said
their attorney, Jessica Kaye. He must stay at least 250 yards away
from him, the order says.
   Inwood played a driven Broadway director in the movie ``Stayin'
Alive.'' When a call was placed Friday to his publicist, a
receptionist said, ``We not commenting on anything.''
   Ms. Kaye said Viner managed Inwood until last year.
   The 35-year-old actress, who this year starred in the NBC-TV
miniseries ``Noble House,'' received the death threats Aug. 16 and
has gone into seclusion for her safety, Ms. Kaye said. The
telephone company traced the calls to Inwood's phone, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who allegedly broke into David
Letterman's house, then claimed to be his wife when she was picked
up driving his car, has been found competent to stand trial. A
prosecutor said Letterman may be called to testify.
   Margaret Ray, 36, was released on her own recognizance Friday.
She is charged with two counts of burglary and one count of car
theft.
   Dr. Sander H. Fogle, a psychiatrist who treated Ray, testified
Friday that she ``has been restored to competency'' and is capable
of assisting in her own defense.
   In May, Ray was stopped at the Lincoln Tunnel between New Jersey
and New York, driving Letterman's blue, 1988 Porsche.
   Ray didn't have the toll money and allegedly told the toll
collector, ``I'm Mrs. David Letterman and this is David Jr. Don't
you think David Letterman is good for the toll?''
   She had allegedly broken into Letterman's New Canaan home and
set up housekeeping several days before the incident. Letterman,
star of NBC's ``Late Night with David Letterman,'' was in
California at the time.
   Authorities initially decided not to press charges at
Letterman's request. But Ray returned to Letterman's house soon
after being released and was rearrested.
   Assistant State's Attorney Philip D'Eromo said the state intends
to prosecute and that Letterman may be called to testify. Letterman
has said he doesn't know the woman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou will stay
hospitalized in London for at least a week undergoing medical tests
for a heart problem, the government said.
   A medical bulletin issued by the government press office Friday
said the 69-year-old premier, who flew to London on Thursday, would
have additional tests to assess the extent of constriction in the
aorta, the main artery that pumps blood to the heart.
   The tests were expected to show whether Papandreou would need
open-heart surgery, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Francisco Quinn pleaded innocent to
felony assault charges for allegedly kicking and seriously injuring
his girlfriend in their West Hollywood apartment.
   The 25-year-old son of actor Anthony Quinn was charged with one
count each of corporal injury to a co-habitant and assault with
force likely to cause great bodily injury. He entered his plea
Friday.
   Quinn, who practiced karate, allegedly kicked Carolyn Greenberg,
23, in the abdomen last October during an argument in their
apartment. She suffered multiple injuries including a ruptured
spleen, authorities said. The couple since has split up,
authorities said.
   The younger Quinn appeared in the film ``Platoon.''
   Pretrial motions were set for Sept. 16. If convicted, the
younger Quinn would face up to seven years in prison. He is free on
$75,000 bail.
