<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NuclearViolations     08-27 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Violations,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virginia Power Fined For Safety Violations At Surry Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SURRY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission fined
Virginia Power $100,000 for safety violations at its Surry nuclear
plant, including an incident in which three workers were exposed to
radiation because a supervisor ``lost track of the time.''
   Friday's decision marked the second time this year the plant has
been fined by the federal agency and the 15th since 1972.
   ``The NRC is concerned that these violations collectively
indicate significant weaknesses in the overall radiation protection
program at the Surry power station,'' J. Nelson Grace, the agency's
regional administrator, said in a letter to the utility.
   Virginia Power said it would not contest the penalty, which is
double the usual fine.
   The fines followed two inspections. The first was conducted
during a routine refueling shutdown in May. The second was after a
maintenance worker was exposed to more radiation than allowed by
federal regulations on May 27.
   During the shutdown, inspectors said workers at the plant were
not properly equipped with monitors when entering high-radiation
areas. The utility also failed to post warning signs that
respirators were required and failed to evaluate adequately the
amount of radioactive material in the air, the NRC said.
   In the second incident, three contract maintenance workers were
exposed to unusually high radiation doses because a Virginia Power
technician ``lost track of the time'' and let them stay in a
high-radiation area for longer than they should have, Virginia
Power spokesman Carl F. Baab said. One of the workers was exposed
to levels higher than NRC standards allow.
</TEXT>
