<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MarchingAgain     08-27 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marching Again,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Back After 25 Years, Marchers See Progress But Lingering Bias</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-March on Washington Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harrison Hawkins was a 20-year-old busboy when
he joined 250,000 civil rights demonstrators in the 1963 March on
Washington where Martin Luther King articulated the dreams of black
Americans.
   Hawkins couldn't eat at the Washington restaurant where he
worked at the time. No blacks were served.
   ``I thought something had to be done about segregation,'' he
said Saturday as he joined a rally marking the 25-year anniversary
of that historic day. ``It was the first time I'd seen that many of
our people _ black people _ get together and do something
positive.''
   Hawkins, now a rigger who handles heavy objects at the
Smithsonian Institution, said he feels good about the progress
that's been made on civil rights in the past quarter-century,
although he says more remains to be done.
   ``In the workplace you see petty things, hidden things.'' he
said. ``It's not direct discrimination, but it's there.''
   Another veteran of the 1963 march who was on hand for Saturday's
anniversary event was 76-year-old Eula Johnson of Washington, who
sat quietly in a shaded lawn chair listening to the speeches.
   She said she left her six children at home and came to the 1963
march because ``I felt that Negroes were making progress and I
wanted to be a part of it. I was raising children at the time and I
wanted them to have the opportunities I thought they should have.''
   Mrs. Johnson said she returned home, picked up her youngest
daughter, 7-year-old Theresa, and took her to a rally later that
day, ``just so she could know how it felt for blacks and white to
be together.''
   Theresa recently died of a stroke at age 32, but not before she
became the only black woman to work in her division at a
telecommunications company, Mrs. Johnson said proudly.
   ``She was able to see the hope before she died,'' she said.
   Naomi and Seymour Wenner, a retired white couple from suburban
Chevy Chase, Md., said they, too, felt drawn to the 1963 march.
   ``It was a great event in my life,'' Wenner, 75, recalled
Saturday. ``Everything was focused on one thing _ civil rights for
Negroes.''
   He said that while Saturday's rally marked the progress made
over the past 25 years, ``there are too many groups taking a free
ride on this _ justice for janitors, this union, that union,
socialist workers, ERA. They're not focused. It isn't what the
memory of Martin Luther King was about.''
   Roselyn Smith-Withers, 38, who is entering Howard University's
School of Divinity, saw Saturday's rally as a celebration that
marked her acceptance of King's message after years of anger and
hurt.
   She was 13 and the only black child in her Long Island, N.Y.,
school when her mother brought her to the 1963 march to hear King
speak.
   ``He articulated the pain that I knew, the fears I had and the
exclusion I was living through,'' she recalled. ``It has been a
force in my life from that point to this day.''
   She said that while her 8-year-old son ``doesn't know the racism
I knew,'' he feels it in other ways.
   ``The major message of this rally is the ongoing fight. I don't
know that it's always accepted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
