<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     08-27 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Of Emergency Ends In Chile For First Time In 15 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government ended the state
of emergency Saturday for the first time since President Gen.
Augusto Pinochet took power in a bloody 1973 coup.
   The lifting of the legislation that severely restricted civil
liberties took effect with the publication of government decrees in
the official bulletin.
   Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez, who last Wednesday announced
the state of emergency would be rescinded, said the restrictions
were no longer needed because order had been re-established
throughout Chile.
   The government lifted the state of emergency and the state of
disruption of internal peace. Combined, they allowed the government
to suspend publication and broadcasts by news media, restrict
public gatherings and labor union activities, and censor mail and
communications.
   Pinochet was empowered to order the arrest and detention of
opponents for up to 20 days; to send into exile citizens considered
dangerous to internal security; to order internal exile for up to
three months and prevent citizens from freely traveling through
Chile.
   The move took effect three days before Chile's top military
leaders meet to nominate a single candidate for a presidential
referendum to be held in early October.
   Pinochet, who is commander of the army, will nominate a
candidate, as will the commanders of the navy, air force and
national police. The 72-year-old general is widely expected to be
nominated for re-election so that he can serve until 1997.
   The government's move, however, was viewed by some as helping to
meet opposition demands for fair play in the presidential
plebiscite.
   But dissidents, while acknowledging it will improve the
political climate, say they will wait to see whether the government
will really allow citizens to exercise the basic liberties that
they were deprived of during the state of emergency.
   Genero Arriagada, a leader of the moderate opposition Christian
Democratic Party, said Saturday, ``This does not erase the 15-year
image of Gen. Pinochet as a dictator.''
   A coalition of socialist groups promptly decided to test the
government's mood by scheduling an opposition rally in Santiago
next week. Before the emergency was lifted, the military had
refused to authorize rallies.
   Another leftist coalition that includes the outlawed Communist
Party also set a rally in Santiago for Sept. 11, the day the
government commemorates the 15th anniversary of the coup that
toppled elected President Salvador Allende. Allende, who died
during the coup, killed himself, the military junta said.
   The political opposition, the Roman Catholic Church and several
foreign governments, including the Reagan administration, have
urged Pinochet to lift the state of a emergency as a basic
condition for a clean referendum.
   In the referendum, about 7.2 million Chileans will vote ``yes''
or ``no'' on the single military-picked candidate. If he is
approved by voters, the candidate will start an eight-year term on
March 11, 1989. If rejected, an open election will be held within a
year, with Pinochet staying in power until then.
   No precise date has been announced for the vote, but Pinochet
and other government officials say it will be held in early October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
