<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Politics     08-27 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Politics,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Announces New Opposition, Rebels Kidnap 28 People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Salvador Laurel
announced a new opposition movement Saturday, claiming President
Corazon Aquino's ``blundering and immoral administration'' would
lead the country to disaster.
   Meanwhile, near the southern city of Zamboanga, Moslem rebels
burned a bus and a car and fled with 28 hostages, the military said.
   Laurel was joined by Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile and representatives
of several opposition groups, including the New Society Movement of
ousted President Ferdinand Marcos, in launching the Union for
National Action.
   ``I accept the honor and the challenge to lead a coalesced
opposition against a blundering and immoral administration that has
betrayed the people,'' Laurel told reporters. ``If (Mrs. Aquino)
continues to run the government, the country is headed for national
disaster.''
   The Union's platform calls for a new treaty on the status of
American military bases in the Philippines that would provide for a
gradual phasing out of the facilities over a 10-year period.
   The Union also called for replacing the U.S.-style presidential
government with a parliamentary system, as well as escalating the
battle against the Communist New People's Army, the armed wing of
the banned Communist Party of the Philippines.
   Mrs. Aquino had no reaction to formation of the Union. On Aug.
13, Laurel called Mrs. Aquino to resign or he would ``dissociate
himself from her government.''
   One week later, Mrs. Aquino said she would remain in office
until her term expires in 1992.
   Laurel ran for vice president with Mrs. Aquino against Marcos in
the 1986 elections. The Marcos-dominated parliament ruled that
Marcos had won the election, but he fled the country for Hawaii on
Feb. 25, 1986, after a civilian-military uprising.
   Mrs. Aquino named Laurel prime minister in her government, but
abolished the post soon afterward. Since then, Laurel has
complained he has been ignored by Mrs. Aquino's advisers.
   Laurel's political fortunes have been declining since September,
when he resigned as foreign secretary and refused to serve in the
Cabinet.
   Enrile, fired as defense minister on Nov. 23, 1986, after a
failed coup by his followers, said Saturday that the Philippines
faced the deepest crisis in its history because of ``a crisis of
leadership.'' He is the only opposition figure in the 23-member
Senate.
   The rebel attack near Zamboanga occurred at dawn on an isolated
stretch of highway on the island of Basilan, 560 miles south of
Manila, according to Lt. Col. Porcawa Dia, regional military
commander.
   Dia said three vehicles carrying 50 people bound for Zamboanga
were stopped by about 30 suspected members of the Moro National
Liberation Front.
   The guerrillas belong to the main faction of Moslem separatist
rebels seeking independence for the southern island of Mindanao.
   Dia said the rebels ordered the passengers to leave the three
vehicles, then set a bus and a car on fire before soldiers arrived,
he said.
   A gunfight broke out, during which eight of the passengers
escaped and 14 others were rescued by soldiers, Dia said. He said
the rebels escaped in the remaining vehicle with the other
passengers and were believed to be hiding in a nearby mountain
village.
   He said the area was cordoned off to prevent the rebels from
escaping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
