<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainWhistles     08-27 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Whistles,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearings Set on Nuisance Train Whistles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howls of protests over train whistles in Chicago
suburbs have reached the ears of the Illinois Commerce Commission,
which plans to take up the issue next week.
   A recently enacted state law requires trains to signal their
approach at all railroad grade crossings. But as train engineers
began complying and tooting at all intersections with roadways,
suburban residents found themselves suffering through sleepless
nights and angry days.
   ``I'm extremely tired and extremely annoyed,'' Mary Krippner of
Westmont said last week. ``Who's going to pay for my nervous
breakdown?''
   The commission on Friday authorized hearings beginning Tuesday
on possible exemptions to the new law.
   In the meantime, a Du Page County judge's temporary order
remains in effect barring four major railroads _ Burlington
Northern, Chicago & North Western, Soo Line and Wisconsin Central _
from sounding whistles in some suburban areas.
   Some of the railroads are interpreting the judge's 10-day order,
issued Thursday, as stretching beyond Du Page County, to the west
of Chicago, so they also have been keeping horns quiet in the
northern and southern suburbs.
   About 500 of the state's 13,000 railroad crossings are at issue
in the ICC hearings, which are expected to run at least two days,
said Bernard Morris, chief railroad engineer for the ICC. Morris
will act as hearing officer and make a recommendation to the
seven-member commission.
   ``I think we're going to hear a lot of people wanting to say
they don't like whistles or they don't want whistles near their
church or near their hospital because it's a nuisance,'' Morris
said Friday.
   He cautioned, however, that the law's wording may limit such
evidence.
   ``It says (exemptions can be granted) if the public is
reasonably and sufficiently protected,'' Morris said. ``It doesn't
say anything about not being able to sleep.''
   Asked whether the state legislature went too far in passing a
blanket whistle-blowing requirment, ICC Chairwoman Mary Meg
Bushnell said, ``I don't think they went overboard. I think they
didn't realize, perhaps what the consequences of this would be.''
   Alfred Ronan, the state representative who proposed the
whistle-blowing requirement, has defended it as a crucial safety
measure.
   ``I was trying to protect the people who don't pay attention
when they go through train stops, and I'd do it again,'' he once
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
