<DOCNO> AP880827-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YellowstoneFireCamp     08-27 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Fire Camp,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Keep Going Thanks To Central Supply Tent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Firefighter Fatigue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It takes a lot to keep a
force of 1,000 firefighters going, and Karla McNary can lay her
hands on just about everything they might need.
   McNary is the distribution leader for the Wolf Lake fire camp
established at Canyon to funnel firefighters onto the Wolf Lake
fire in Yellowstone.
   From row after row of cardboard boxes stacked in her blue and
white tent, she can pull sleeping bags, fire resistant clothing,
gloves, goggles, hard hats, and fire hoses, of which more than
12,000 feet was dispensed Friday alone.
   There are also shovels; Pulaskis, a tool that is a cross between
an ax and a hoe; MREs _ meals ready to eat; and fire shelters.
Behind these piles are more piles of ground sheets, chainsaw kits,
chainsaw oil, earplugs, water jugs, files to sharpen the tools and
garbage cans.
   And then there are the drip torches, for starting backfires, and
kerosene lamps, to see by when you come off the fire lines after
sundown.
   McNary also has to keep track of all that gear.
   ``If it doesn't come back, then the crew that had it last is
responsible for it,'' she said in an interview late Friday. ``You
have to know exactly who's got it, when they're taking it, and when
they're bringing it back.''
   What's the most popular item in her inventory? Sleeping bags,
and not your average down or synthetic bag. These are made out of
paper, according to McNary.
   ``They go like wildfire,'' she said, realizing too late the pun
she made.
   Although made of paper, the bags endure a dry cleaning after one
use and are ready to go again.
   ``After that one cleaning, they throw them in the garbage,''
said McNary. ``They're just paper, regular paper. It's not much,
but it'll keep you warm.''
   But for real warmth in Yellowstone, where the night temperatures
in late August can dip into the low 30s, there's nothing like a
cardboard box, she said.
   ``A lot of people, to keep really warm, they'll sleep in
boxes,'' McNary said, explaining that the boxes left after the
equipment is doled out are quite popular with the firefighters.
   ``You improvise,'' she added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
