<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Marches With Jackson In King Tribute; Bush In Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New info in top 11 grafs including Jackson remarks, Bush
campaign explanation of no being at march; pickup 8th graf, ``I
mean xxx
^By JERRY ESTILL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis linked up with one-time Democratic presidential
challenger Jesse Jackson on Saturday for a quarter-century tribute
to Martin Luther King Jr. on the steamy hot steps of the Lincoln
Memorial.
   George Bush campaigned in Texas where his spokeswoman said he
had already agreed to address a Marine veterans group in Dallas
before being invited to participate in the Washington march.
   Press secretary Shelia Tate said the Bush campaign sent regrets,
and dispatched Bush's son Marvin to attend the march.
   Without mentioning the Reagan administration by name, Dukakis
said many of the late civil rights leader's dreams remain
unfulfilled and promised to work to change that if elected
president.
   ``We cannot look back or look down when we know that the cancer
of racism and bigotry is still with us and that over the healed
wounds of the past new wounds are opening in our cities and in our
suburbs,'' he said.
   ``We have to look up, because that march for good jobs and real
freedom didn't end that August afternoon 25 years ago. We have to
march on.''
   A crowd estimated by U.S. Park Police at about 30,000 gave
Dukakis a friendly reception and there were chants of ``Where is
George?'' after his speech.
   However, the warmest response was for Jackson, who did not speak
until after Dukakis had departed and did not mention the Democratic
presidential ticket specifically.
   But Jackson urged his followers to vote and it was clear it did
not mean for them to vote for the Republican ticket.
   ``George Bush is not in Washington today,'' he said. ``He must
not be here for the Inauguration next January.''
   Bush's decision to campaign in Texas emphasized his
determination to go all-out to win what his campaign chief termed
the must win state of all must win states.
   ``I mean to run hard to run hard, I mean to fight hard and I
mean to win Texas,'' Bush told a rally of party workers at Houston
hotel.
   The vice president praised his running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, and told the qroup he ``is going to be a tremendous asset
to this ticket and I am proud to have placed my bet on the future.''
   ``We have a new generation,'' Bush said. ``This man will measure
up.''
   He then left for a couple of late afternoon stops with campaign
chairman James Baker. It was Bush's first trip to Texas since Bush
was annointed the Republican presidential nominee in New Orleans
less than two weeks ago.
   Baker told reporters the election is ``one hell of a lot more
winnable (for Bush) than a lot of sages were saying just two weeks
ago.''
   ``If there was ever a `must' state for a presidential election,
Texas is it in 1988,'' Baker added.
   As if to underscore that strategic assessment, the Democratic
vice presidential nominee, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, wrapped up a
five-day campaign swing with an appearance at Austin, the capital
of his home state, before flying back to Washington. He attacked
Bush for what he termed ``an outrageous misrepresentation'' about
Dukakis.
   ``George Bush comes to Texas, goes to Longview, and charges Mike
Dukakis with being soft on the war on drugs,'' said Bentsen. ``That
is an outrageous misrepresentation of the facts.''
   Bentsen said the homicide rate in Massachusetts under Dukakis'
governorship is half the national average, that Dukakis has added
1,500 law enforcement personnel, and has pushed programs to help
victims of crime.
   ``I don't think (Dukakis' record) has been surpassed by any
other state in the nation,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Quayle was in California expressing confidence that
his campaign is getting off the dime after being bogged down by
questions about his National Guard service.
   At a news conference in Irvine, Quayle said he was pleased with
the response from the crowds during his first week on the campaign
trail by himself.
   ``I really feel a great deal of enthusiasm beginning to build,''
he said.
   Quayle was asked about comments by his wife, Marilyn, aired
Friday night on ABC's ``20-20'' suggesting that the media was out
to get her husband because he is a conservative.
   ``I am not going to disagree with Marilyn. Marilyn is my best
adviser and my strongest supporter,'' Quayle said.
   Pressed to say whether he believed the media was against him,
Quayle said, ``I just hope that the press will begin to focus on
the issues of this campaign.''
   Mrs. Quayle said she stood by her comments on the television
interview that the press had engaged in ``overkill'' in its
coverage of her husband. In New Orleans last week, she said ``we
had a real feeding frenzy'' by media, which has abated only
slightly.
   Quayle traveled to several rallies in California and a state
fair in Sacramento.
</TEXT>
