<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Capitol     08-27 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Capitol,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lengthy Sting Described By Informant's Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HOWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents aided by a state Senate
staff member mounted a two-year sting to uncover corruption in the
Legislature, forming dummy companies that lured lawmakers with
bribes, a lawyer close to the investigation says.
   The investigation began when John A. Shahabian, facing
allegations of wrongdoing arising out of an earlier FBI probe,
agreed to cooperate with the FBI and assisted in recording
legislators engaged in allegedly illegal acts, Donald Heller,
Shahabian's attorney, said Friday.
   Shahabian was snared in the earlier FBI sting and told
authorities he would cooperate in an expanded probe into bribery
and extortion, Heller said.
   ``For years and years, there has been widespread corruption in
the Legislature ... a cesspool,'' Heller said. ``My client was
initially caught up in it and came forward and cooperated for two
years.''
   Lawmakers who were ``rumored to be on the take,'' were offered
illicit donations, Heller added, ``and sure enough, they took the
bait.'' He described the sting as ``creative and inventive.''
   Shahabian, a staff member of the state Senate Elections
Committee, pretended to be a part owner of one of the dummy
companies, Peachstate Capital West, a shadowy venture capital
company located above a store 1{ blocks from the Capitol. The other
two ``owners'' of the company were FBI agents, Heller said.
   Heller did not identify the lawmakers who were videotaped but
said he expected ``dozens of indictments soon.'' He did not
elaborate.
   Terry Knowles, agent in charge of the Sacramento FBI office,
said arrests in the case were not expected ``at the present time.''
   Late Wednesday and early Thursday, 30 federal agents with
warrants descended on the Capitol and searched the offices of four
lawmakers and their aides, seeking materials related to two obscure
bills. Both measures had been vetoed by Gov. George Deukmejian,
who, unaware of the sting operation, described them as unwarranted
special interest bills.
   Capitol sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
four legislators whose offices were searched were Democratic
Assemblywoman Gwen Moore of Los Angeles, who wrote the two bills;
Republican Assemblymen Frank Hill of Whittier and Pat Nolan of
Glendale; and Democratic Sen. Joseph Montoya of El Monte.
   Nolan, the Republican leader of the Assembly, offered to resign
his leadership post Friday at a closed-door meeting in the wake of
the investigation, the San Francisco Examiner reported Saturday.
   Heller made the comments in a telephone interview from Hawaii,
where he was on vacation. Shahabian, who has declined to speak with
reporters, is also ``on a short vacation,'' Heller said.
</TEXT>
