<2ND_LINE>AM-Von Bulow Mansion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>History Comes With von Bulow Mansion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th, `Von Bulow...' to add that judge
handling case because Mrs. Von Bulow in coma, picks up 6th graf
pvs, `Last December...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has accepted an antique dealer's
$4.2 million offer for the 21-room mansion where Claus von Bulow
once lived with heiress Martha ``Sunny'' von Bulow.
   The oceanfront estate, Clarendon Court, is home to a prince and
princess and includes the three-story main house, an 18-room
carriage house, three fountains and a swimming pool.
   A New York judge overseeing the sale on Thursday accepted the
offer submitted by Glenn C. Randall of Washington, D.C.
   The mansion, which was built for the owner of the Pullman Car
Co., is owned by Mrs. von Bulow, 57, who has been in what doctors
describe as an irreversible coma since suffering a seizure at the
mansion eight years ago.
   Von Bulow, 62, was convicted of charges he tried to kill his
wife with injections of insulin and other drugs, but was acquitted
at a second trial in June 1985. He stood to inherit about $14
million of Mrs. von Bulow's Pittsburg utilities fortune, valued
then at $75 million.
   A committee handles Mrs. von Bulow's financial affairs because
of her condition. The judge's approval was needed for the sale.
   Last December, von Bulow agreed to divorce his wife and to
renounce all claims to her money in an out-of-court settlement to a
lawsuit filed by his stepchildren, Prince Alexander von Auersperg
and Princess Annie-Laurie ``Ala'' Auersperg Kneissl. They charged
that the Danish-born socialite had tried to kill and defraud their
mother.
   In exchange, the von Bulows' daughter, Cosima, was restored as
full heiress to one-third of her maternal grandmother's $100
million estate. The 20-year-old had been cut out of Annie-Laurie
Aitken's will for siding with her father in the family feud.
   Clarendon Court is not without its lesser-known tragedies as
well. In August 1982, Paul E. Molitor Jr., the late executive
director of the Newport Preservation Society, was living as von
Bulow's guest in the carriage house when he committed suicide.
   Despite, or perhaps because of, its sordid past, Clarendon Court
was much sought after when it went on the market in late June.
   ``There were almost continuous appointments for the couple of
weeks'' it was listed, said Robert Corbin, owner of Private
Properties. ``The publicity surrounding the von Bulow family was
very instrumental'' in its appeal.
   Mrs. von Bulow remains in New York's Columbia-Presbyterian
Hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
