<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-27 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Scattered Around Nation, Unusually Hot On West Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain extended over parts of the South, the Southwest and
sections of the Plains on Saturday, and the Pacific states had
unseasonably hot weather.
   Showers and thunderstorms outlined the eastern edge of cooler
air pressing across the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern
two-thirds of the Plains. Behind the front, temperatures at noon
were only in the 50s and 60s.
   Showers and thunderstorms reached from Wisconsin across
Illinois, the central Missouri Valley, Kansas, western Oklahoma,
eastern Colorado, the Texas Panhandle and northeastern New Mexico.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from southern Nevada
across Arizona, and from the coast of the Carolinas across Florida
and along the lower Texas Gulf Coast.
   Thunderstorms produced more than an inch of rain around
Charleston, S.C., causing local flooding around North Charleston
and Summerville, the National Weather Service said.
   A flash flood warning was posted for sections of northwest and
north-central Arizona, where thunderstorms moved over ground that
had been saturated by an inch or more of rain during the previous
48 hours.
   In the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 2.96 inches of rain fell near
Tampa, Fla., and 2.47 inches fell at Gainesville, Fla.
   A tropical storm watch was posted over the northwestern and
central Bahamas, because of a tropical depression centered about
125 miles east-southeast of Miami and moving toward the northwest.
   Temperatures over the Pacific states were warmer than
seasonable, reaching up to 90 over the Washington coast and more
than 100 across the desert Southwest during the morning.
   North-central Texas also had a few highs around 100, and highs
were in the 90s in much of Arkansas and from Alabama across Texas
into Oklahoma.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55 at
Crescent City, Calif., and Ely, Minn., to 105 at Palm Springs,
Calif. The nation's low Saturday morning was 33 at Butte, Mont.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
northern and western New York state across western Pennsylvania,
Michigan, the lower Ohio Valley, southern Illinois, southern
Missouri, Arkansas, northern Texas, southeastern New Mexico and
western Texas, as well as from the Virginia coast across central
Florida, and scattered from central Arizona into southern Utah.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted over the upper Great
Lakes, the northern two-thirds of the Mississippi Valley, the
northern and central Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, central
Arizona, and along the central coast of California; in the 90s from
southern New Jersey across the Carolinas and from the Tennessee
Valley across the central Gulf of Mexico states, southern Arkansas
through Louisiana, much of Texas, southern New Mexico, the Pacific
Northwest and the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah; in the
upper 90s across central and southeastern Texas; in the 90s to
about 110 from the desert Southwest across eastern California into
southwestern Oregon; and generally in the 80s over the remainder of
the nation.
</TEXT>
