<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TridentLaunch     08-27 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trident Launch,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trident Missile Launched Successfully</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trident 2 submarine missile
vaulted off a launch pad Saturday and successfully hurled an
unarmed warhead package to an ocean target, the Navy reported.
   It was the 12th success in 14 test firings for the three-stage,
$23.7 million missile being developed as the most powerful in the
Navy's nuclear arsenal.
   The Navy reported 10 minutes after the 4:04 p.m. EDT launch that
the test had been successful. The last Trident 2 launching, on July
7, ended when the missile veered off course and was destroyed by a
radio signal from the Air Force range safety officer.
   The 44-foot weapon has a range of nearly 6,000 miles, but
officials declined to disclose how far the test warhead package
traveled Saturday.
   Six more land pad tests are planned here, to be followed by at
least five launches from submerged submarines. The weapon is
scheduled to become operational and join the fleet late next year.
   Each Trident 2 is designed to hurl up to 10 nuclear warheads to
different targets. There will be 24 of the missiles aboard each
Trident submarine.
</TEXT>
