<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-'68Revisited     08-27 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-'68 Revisited,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoffman, Seale and Others Celebrate 20th Anniversary of Convention
Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graying, but for the most part still true to
their ideals, activists who demonstrated at the tumultuous 1968
Democratic National convention gathered Saturday to commemorate the
20th anniversary of the protests.
   ``It took quite a while to get here, but here we are,'' said
former Yippie Abbie Hoffman.
   About 400 people gathered in the 17,000-seat International
Amphitheater, where the convention was held. Then-Chicago Mayor
Richard J. Daley banned the demonstrators from the facility in 1968.
   Most of the participants _ including former Students for a
Democratic Society President Carl Oglesby and former Chicago Seven
defendants Hoffman and David Dellinger _ agreed that while the
goals they sought remain largely unfulfilled, their movement and
the Chicago protests had a positive effect on the country.
   ``What I saw and experienced in Chicago _ the police unleashed
like stormtroopers ... seeing that repression, seeing that
violence, and then seeing the response _ the fact that Mayor Daley
didn't scare us out of Chicago ... For the first time, I thought,
`I'm not a radical, I'm not a reformer. I'm a revolutionary,'' said
Stew Albert.
   ``We caused a lot of things to actually happen and change. We
broke down a lot of the racial barriers,'' added Bobby Seale, who
was ordered bound and gagged when he stood trial on conspiracy
charges stemming from the demonstrations.
   ``I'm very proud of my history. I don't regret one nickel of
it,'' said Seale, 51, now involved in minority recruitment at
Temple University in Philadelphia.
   ``I think we had a tremendous impact in sticking up for the
right to protest,'' said Hoffman, 51, a perennial activist who
calls himself ``an American dissident.''
   ``The incidents that happened here changed the way that police
forces are trained in America today,'' Hoffman said.
   During the 1968 convention, hundreds of protesters fought with
police in downtown Grant Park after Daley said they would not be
allowed to march to the amphitheater.
   Eight protest leaders were indicted on charges of conspiracy to
incite violence. They were known as the Chicago Seven because Seale
was tried separately.
   The atmosphere in the hall Saturday was a far cry from Aug. 26,
1968, when the Democratic convention formally opened. This time the
hall houses scores of sympathizers for those who were once barred,
and many of them set up tables to promote causes ranging from
Maoists to the Free Puerto Rico Committee and the League of Women
Voters.
   Only about 40 of those attending the conference participated in
the protests. Others said they were there for a sense of history.
   ``They're real history makers that I've studied,'' said Valerie
Yoshimura, a junior at the University of California at Santa
Barbara who was born two weeks before the convention. ``We have a
lot to learn from them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
