<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Daniell     08-27 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Daniell,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Legislator Eugene Daniell Dies At 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eugene Daniell, a self-proclaimed champion
of the underdog who once tear-gassed the New York Stock Exchange
and was known for his oratory in the state Legislature, has died at
age 83.
   The maverick nine-term state representative died Friday, said
Franklin Memorial Hospital spokeswoman Marcia Hansen. She would not
disclose the cause of death.
   Daniell, who retired from the Legislature in 1986, practiced a
stirring oratory style compared to that of unsuccessful
turn-of-the-century presidential candidate William Jennings Bryan.
But his politics were like those of Louisiana's populist U.S.
senator and governor, Huey Long, with whom Daniell briefly worked
until Long was assassinated in 1935.
   Throughout his career Daniell fought for redistributing
America's wealth. In 1933, he opened tear gas canisters near
ventilators in the New York Stock Exchange, and then waited to be
arrested. Unable to come up with a $500 fine, Daniell served 30
days in jail.
   ``As I saw it, that was the one institution that contributed
more than anything to the imbalance,'' Daniell said in a 1985
interview.
   After Long died, Daniell established a one-man law office in
Franklin.
   He was elected to his first of seven terms as mayor in 1948. The
following year, he was elected to the state Senate for one term. He
first won election to the House in 1961. He also waged several
unsuccessful campaigns for Congress on shoestring budgets.
   He was known for having compared President Reagan to Hitler,
pushing a resolution to recommend impeaching President Nixon, and
wearing his Army uniform as he marched in demonstrations against
the Vietnam War.
   After his wife, Eva, died in 1982 after much suffering, Daniell
fought for ``living will'' legislation allowing people to sign a
document barring the use of extraordinary means to continue life.
The Legislature eventually overrode Gov. John Sununu's veto of the
measure.
   He is survived by a son, Eugene Daniell of Concord. No funeral
was planned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
