<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LibertyProtest     08-27 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberty Protest,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Castro Protest in Statue of Liberty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men protesting what they called the
executions of more than 400 people under Cuban President Fidel
Castro's regime handcuffed themselves to a handrail in the Statue
of Liberty's crown Saturday.
   The men stood in line with tourists about two hours before
climbing to the top of the statue.
   Police clipped the cuffs after about an hour, cited the men for
assembling without a permit and ordered them to leave. They left
Liberty Island by ferry, said Tom Bradley, deputy superintendent of
the Statue of Liberty National Monument.
   The men wanted to call attention to an incident on Aug. 30,
1962, when ``more than 400 people were executed by a firing squad
under orders of Castro,'' said Saul Pedrera, a spokesman for the
protesters.
   The Statue of Liberty was chosen because it is a well-known
symbol of freedom, Pedrera said. No one was hurt and the protesters
were carrying no weapons.
   The men, who ranged in age from 48 to 58, were not arrested, but
were ordered to post $150 bond each within 10 days.
   Some 18,000 visitors were expected at on Liberty Island on
Saturday.
</TEXT>
