<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TelephoneBandit     08-27 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Telephone Bandit,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Looting Pay Telephones Arrested in Orange County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENA PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of stealing more than
$500,000 from pay telephones and who twice was the subject on the
``America's Most Wanted'' television program has been arrested.
   James Clark, 49, of Peninsula, Ohio, was arrested Friday night
following a three-year, nationwide search, police said.
   Clark's arrest at an undisclosed residence in this Orange County
community, about 20 miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles, was
unrelated to his mentions on the Fox network's crime program, said
Lawrence G. Lawler, special agent in charge of the FBI's Los
Angeles office.
   ``He may not be `Jack the Ripper,''' Lawler said, ``but he is a
one-of-a-kind thief. His total take exceeds half a million dollars.
We're glad to have him in custody.''
   An FBI spokesman said Clark was arrested without resistence, but
would not say what led agents to find him.
   Clark allegedly picked locks to remove coins from phones, the
FBI said.
   Clark was arrested on a fugitive warrant from Ohio. He was being
held at the federal prison at Terminal Island and was to appear
before a U.S. magistrate in Los Angeles on Monday, the FBI said.
   ``America's Most Wanted'' capsulizes real, unsolved crimes.
Viewers are asked to contact local law enforcement agencies if they
have information concerning the crimes.
</TEXT>
