<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Navajo-Hopi     08-27 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navajo-Hopi,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navajo Chairman Defies Hopi Tribe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEESTO, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Navajo Indians led by Tribal
Chairman Peter MacDonald defied the Hopi Tribe and a congressional
mandate Saturday and began repairing homes located on Hopi land.
   The Navajo-Hopi Relocation Act of 1974 partitioned some 1.8
million acres of land that once was occupied by both tribes. The
Hopis have left land assigned to the Navajos, but about 200 Navajo
families refuse to leave land now designated as Hopi.
   Federal officials and Hopi Chairman Ivan Sidney contended the
Navajos should get permission from the Hopi Tribe before making
repairs to those homes, but MacDonald said Navajos would not
consent to relocation, as the Hopis wanted in return for permission.
   MacDonald, wearing a brand new tool belt and blue jeans rather
than his customary three-piece suit, watched as tribal employees
and volunteers put a new roof and windows in a home owned by
Jeannie Paddock, 75.
   Other volunteers worked on homes elsewhere on the land, the
ownership of which has been disputed by the two tribes for more
than a century. Some repair plans went awry as rain turned dirt
roads into mud bogs, and two cement mixers sank to their hubs.
   MacDonald said crews would continue work Sunday and Monday,
beginning with homes in the greatest state of disrepair.
   ``These families have a right to repair their houses,'' he said.
``These people don't want to leave. They believe they belong here.''
   He added that he feared Navajo children and elderly tribal
members could die if their homes were not repaired before the onset
of a cold winter.
   Sidney said MacDonald should provide homes on Navajo land if
he's so concerned about his tribe's well-being.
   ``MacDonald talks about relieving hardships and building houses
on our land, but if he is really worried about relieving hardships,
why can't he build them homes on his side?'' Sidney said Friday.
   But MacDonald said people like Mrs. Paddock do not want to leave
their traditional homes and Mrs. Paddock, speaking through an
interpreter, agreed.
   ``For many years I have been asking for repairs,'' she said.
``This is our land. This is where we were born and we're going to
resist. We're not going anywhere.''
   Sidney has said the Hopis will go to court to seek a restraining
order against MacDonald.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
