<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newspage-LittleLeague     08-27 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage-Little League,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Far East Wins Fifth Consecutive Title</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Far East team won the 42nd Little
League World Series Saturday _ the fifth year in a row _ as Tai
Chung, Taiwan, defeated Pearl City, Hawaii, 10-0, behind the
pitching of Chen-Lung Yu.
   Yu relied on a 75 mph fastball against the Hawaii team.
   ``He was really throwing hard,'' Pearl City coach Richard Numata
said. ``I guess he was a little bit too strong for us.''
   Yu, a 5-foot-4{-inch, 134-pound right-hander, pitched all six
innings, striking out 10 while walking one. He retired the last 17
batters in order.
   Manager Ta-Yuan Lai said Yu picked up confidence as the game
went along.
   ``In the first inning he was not as stable as he was
afterwards,'' said Lai, who managed the 1981 Little League champion
from Tai Chung.
   Chris Yoshimoto had the only hit for Pearl City, a community of
40,000 people near Pearl Harbor.
   Pearl City starter Ryan Morioka was the losing pitcher. The
4-foot-11, 91-pound righthander allowed two runs on two hits, using
mostly a curveball.
   An estimated 20 million people watched the game on ABC-TV.
   Tai Chung is a city of 700,000 people in central Taiwan.
   Teams from Taiwan have won the series for three consecutive
years, outscoring their American opponents 41-3.
   Korean teams won the championship in 1984 and 1985. Far East
teams have won 18 of the past 22 years.
</TEXT>
