<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan 2ndLd-Writethru   08-27 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0564,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Reported Holding Two Cities, Battling Over Two Others</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, `They said...' with two grafs to CORRECT that
rebels have laid siege but not captured Kunduz and Khandahar,
reflecting lead; picks up 9th graf pvs: Rebel commanders...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas held two Afghan
provincial capitals Saturday and battled communist soldiers for two
more as they struggled to tighten their hold around Kabul, rebel
leaders and Western diplomats said.
   Meanwhile, Tass reported from Moscow that the rebels killed four
people, including two children, in a rocket attack on the Kabul,
the Afghan capital. The official Soviet news agency said the
``barbaric'' attack wounded 12.
   Rebels have been increasing their rocket attacks on Kabul since
Soviet troops began withdrawing from Afghanistan on May 15.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
guerrillas captured the city of Bamyan, about 70 miles northwest of
Kabul, in mid-August.
   Official Radio Kabul said government forces had to ``change the
status of their deployment'' in central Bamyan province after
several days of fighting with the rebels. It did not elaborate.
   Taloqan, the capital of northern Takhar province, has been in
guerrilla hands since Aug. 15, when the Soviets said they reached
the halfway point of their troop withdrawal from Afghanistan, the
sources said.
   They said guerrillas overran the city of Kunduz in neighboring
Kunduz province about the middle of August, but government forces,
with heavy Soviet air support, wrested it back several days later.
   Since then, the rebels have again laid siege to Kunduz and the
southeastern provincial capital of Kandahar but have not captured
them, the sources said.
   Rebel commanders say their strategy is to take the provincial
capitals, then to stage an assault on Kabul, the fortress-like
capital that is expected to be the last stronghold of the departing
Soviet army.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
communist government fight the U.S.-backed guerrillas. On April 14,
the Soviet Union agreeed to withdraw its estimated 100,000 troops
beginning May 15, 1988 and ending Feb. 15, 1989.
   At the Shindand air base in western Afghanistan, Soviet and
Afghan troops recently clashed over the alleged rape of an Afghan
woman, according to Agency Afghan Press, a Pakistan-based
pro-guerrilla news service.
   In another incident, two Soviets, three Afghans and an Indian
landed two Soviet helicopter gunships inside the Pakistani border
Wednesday and asked for asylum, according to the semi-official
Pakistani News Agency. Pakistani authorities Friday denied the
report.
   Guerrilla leaders mourned the loss of their Pakistani supporter,
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, who died in a plane crash Aug. 17
that also killed U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 others.
   The guerrillas and some Pakistani officials have blamed the
crash on sabotage by agents of the Kabul government.
   ``The late Zia is a victim of the Afghan holy war, who possesses
a lofty place in the caravan of Afghan martyrs,'' said guerrilla
leader Gulbaddin Hekmatyar in a statement Saturday.
   Zia, an army general, championed the guerrillas' cause and
offered Pakistani territory for their training and supplies. The
new government, under acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, has
pledged to continue Zia's policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
