<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   08-27 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0591,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoners Riot; Leaders Call For Interim Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The broadcast...' with two new grafs to
add reference to Friday BBC report of 1,000 killed; picks up 7th
pvs: Authorities at...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 prisoners escaped from a
southern jail Saturday and 36 were killed trying to flee another
prison, state radio said. A popular former defense minister joined
calls for an interim government to end nationwide turmoil and
restore democracy.
   Unrest continued after massive demonstrations this month ended
26 years of authoritarian rule. Mob lootings were reported in
several areas, including the capital, where 150 people stole 7,000
gallons of fuel from a railway station.
   State-run Rangoon radio said more than 500 prisoners overpowered
guards early Saturday to flee from their jail in Mergui, 350 miles
southeast of Rangoon. It was the third mass prison escape in three
days.
   The radio said that on Friday, guards at the Insein jail, eight
miles north of central Rangoon, fired on 2,000 prisoners who set
fire to buildings and tried to break open the gates.
   ``Prison personnel had to control the situation and unavoidably
had to shoot,'' the radio said. ``As a result, 36 prisoners were
killed and 103 injured.''
   The British Broadcasting Corp. had reported Friday that the
rebellion at Insein left about 1,000 dead, but that report could
not be independently verified.
   The Rangoon radio broadcast said all buildings at the jail
burned to the ground but did not say if the rioting was over. Some
injured prisoners remained untreated because they tried to prevent
medics from entering the prison.
   Authorities at Insein also released at least 655 prisoners, some
because they were nearing the end of their sentences and some for
good conduct.
   The radio also reported prison riots Wednesday at Bassein, 90
miles west of Rangoon, where one inmate was killed and 100 escaped,
and Thursday in the Arrakan state bordering Bangladesh, where six
inmates were killed and about 1,600 escaped.
   Tin Oo, a popular former defense minister and retired general,
told about 50,000 people in Rangoon on Saturday that Burma needs a
transitional government now to end the month-long turmoil that has
toppled two leaders, sparked almost daily protests nationwide and,
by official count, killed at least 112 people.
   ``Following the recent public demonstrations against the
one-party regime, the light of democracy has now been visible,''
Tin Oo said.
   ``The situation in the country is still very delicate with
demonstrations continuing in many cities,'' he said. ``I therefore
urge the government to immediately form an interim government to
ease the situation and ... to prepare for democratic reforms.''
   The widely respected Tin Oo, 62, was removed as defense minister
and army chief in 1976 by former leader Ne Win. Once considered the
third most powerful official with a strong military following, he
was jailed after an investigation into an alleged plot against the
government.
   Thakin Soe, a former communist leader, issued a statement from
his hospital bed calling for multiparty democracy and demanding an
interim government to restore peace.
   Thakin Soe formed the now obsolete ultra-radical Communist Party
of Burma in 1937.
   The turmoil in Burma began July 23 with the resignation of
77-year-old Ne Win, who took over in a military coup in 1962 and
presided with an iron hand over Burma's economic destruction. The
Burma Socialist Program Party, the country's only party, named
hardliner Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   During demonstrations against Sein Lwin, hated by the public for
his alleged brutal suppression of dissent, army troops fired into
crowds of protesters. The government said 112 were killed, but
diplomats said the toll may be much higher.
   Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12, and was replaced Aug. 19 by Maung
Maung, the first civilian president in 26 years.
   But even Maung Maung's announcement Wednesday that he would
recommend a popular referendum on one-party rule has not ended
protests.
   Rallies have been peaceful since Sein Lwin quit, but law and
order has deteriorated since Maung Maung lifted martial law
Wednesday.
   ``Security in the city ... isn't so good, especially after the
darkness comes on,'' said an Asian diplomat. ``The streets are
nearly empty at night. Theft and looting cases are reported
incessantly.''
   The government has been silent on the most recent protests and
on the stream of demands from prominent figures for immediate
democracy. That silence along with deterioriating social conditions
has provoked rumors that Ne Win and other officials may be
preparing to flee Burma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
