<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLO 1stLd-Writethru   08-27 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0586,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Asks UN To Protect Palestinians In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th graf to UPDATE with PLO
statement; picks up 6th pvs: Arafat has...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser
Arafat on Saturday asked the United Nations to play a larger role
in protecting Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   ``There was a long discussion about all aspects of the
Palestinian question,'' U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar told reporters after a 90-minute private session with
Arafat at the U.N. office here.
   ``He conveyed to me his concern about the fate of the
Palestinians in the occupied territories, which I do share,'' Perez
de Cuellar said.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8 in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip, more than 250 Palestinians have been killed,
most by Israeli gunfire. Four Israelis also have died.
   Perez de Cuellar said the PLO chief also raised ``other
political aspects of the problem.'' He did not elaborate.
   A statement issued by the PLO Saturday said Arafat, during the
meeting with the U.N. chief, ``stressed the need for immediate
international measures to ensure the protection of the Palestinian
people and also to provide for their support.''
   The statement also said Arafat briefed Perez de Cuellar on steps
taken by the PLO ``to assert the sovereignty of the Palestinian
people over its homeland and the assumption by the PLO of its full
responsibilities as the sole legitimate representative of the
Palestinian people.''
   Arafat has floated the idea of asking for a U.N. peacekeeping
force in the occupied territories if the Arab-Israeli conflict is
settled. A PLO official said before the meeting that Arafat would
explore ways of involving the world body directly in the
territories, including a possible trusteeship.
   One agenda topic was believed to be the possible creation of a
provisional Palestinian government and proclamation of independence
in the territories occupied by Israel since the 1967 Middle East
war and home to 1.5 million Palestinians.
   A related issue would be securing international recognition of
such a state. The PLO is backing its claim with a 1947 Security
Council resolution envisioning a Palestine partitioned into
separate Jewish and Arab states.
   Arafat also was expected to urge stronger involvement of the
U.N. in efforts to call an international Middle East peace
conference.
   The uprising and the July 31 decision by King Hussein of Jordan
to sever ties with the West Bank and Gaza have led the PLO to take
a more active role in the territories.
   A special meeting of the Palestine National Council, the
Palestinians' parliament in exile, was expected to discuss the
independence issue the middle of next month, but a top PLO official
said Saturday in Tunis the session probably will be put off until
after September.
   On Friday, the U.N. Security Council issued a statement backed
by all 15 members expressing concern over Israeli policies in the
occupied territories.
   The statement spoke of a ``grave and serious situation resulting
from the closing-off of areas, the imposition of curfews and the
consequent increase'' in dead and injured.
   The council also demanded that Israel stop deporting Palestinian
civilians from the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
