<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolicemanCharged     08-27 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Policeman Charged,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Policeman Killed Neighbor After Long Grudge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EPPING, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer has been charged with
murder in the shotgun death of a neighbor that authorities said
stemmed from a 14-year-old grudge.
   Robert A. McLaughlin, 47, an 18-year veteran of the Hampton
Police Department, surrendered to state police Friday and confessed
to killing real estate broker Robert Cushing in June, said Barbara
Keshen, an assistant attorney general.
   A district court judge arraigned McLaughlin on a first-degree
murder charge Saturday at Portsmouth Hospital, where he was being
treated for high blood pressure. McLaughlin was being held without
bail.
   Keshen said at a news conference that the shooting apparently
stemmed from an incident about 14 years ago in which McLaughlin
made a misdemeanor arrest and Cushing became involved indirectly.
Keshen gave no further details of that incident.
   ``Since that period of time (McLaughlin) had evidently harbored
ill will feelings against Mr. Cushing that seem to have come to a
head on the evening of June 1, where he admitted that he took his
shotgun, loaded it, went over to the Cushing residence and shot Mr.
Cushing,'' Keshen said.
   Cushing, 63, was shot when he answered his front door.
   Hampton Police Chief Robert Mark said in a telephone interview
that he could not comment on the case, but he described McLaughlin
as a ``model policeman. He had a very good record.''
   ``He was what you wanted cops to be _ sharp, clean cut,'' Mark
said.
</TEXT>
