<HEAD>GOP Nominee Says His Comfort Zone Rising</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``Quayle traveled
...'' to UPDATE with later appearances. Picks up 8th graf pvs,
bgng: ``At the ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said Saturday he is
pleased with the response from crowds during his first week on the
campaign trail by himself.
   ``I really feel a great deal of enthusiasm beginning to build,''
the Republican vice presidential nominee said at a news conference.
   Quayle was asked about comments by his wife, Marilyn, aired
Friday night on ABC's ``20-20'' suggesting that the media was out
to get her husband because he is a conservative.
   ``I am not going to disagree with Marilyn. Marilyn is my best
adviser and my strongest supporter,'' Quayle said.
   Pressed to say whether he believed the media was against him,
Quayle said, ``I just hope that the press will begin to focus on
the issues of this campaign.''
   Mrs. Quayle said she stood by her comments on the television
interview that the press had engaged in ``overkill'' in its
coverage of her husband. In New Orleans last week, she said ``we
had a real feeding frenzy'' by media, which has abated only
slightly.
   Quayle traveled to several rallies in California and a state
fair in Sacramento.
   At Lake Mission Viejo Park, Quayle got a rousing reception from
the audience, which carried signs reading ``Pro-Lifers for Quayle''
and ``I don't Love the Liberal Media.''
   He warned them that a victory by Michael Dukakis would mean a
return to the economic doldrums and the weakness of national
security during the Carter years.
   ``If America liked Jimmy Carter, they are going to love Michael
Dukakis,'' he said.
   At the California State Fair, Quayle hopped on an antique
reaping machine and pitched hay. He then drove a tractor, telling
reporters afterward, ``I haven't done this in a long time.''
   He also presented ribbons to a group of 4-H teens, who had
trained guide dogs for the blind.
   When he handed a ribbon to one student, he bent and pet her dog,
a black Labrador retriever named Madonna, who sat up and licked his
face.
   When he got to the next dog, however, the animal just lay on the
ground without reacting.
   ``Now I know how it feels to be hounded,'' Quayle quipped.
   At the news conference, Quayle reiterated his position that
there is nothing left to ask or answer about his membership in the
Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam war.
   ``There have been a lot of innuendoes out there over the last
few weeks implying that somehow there was undue influence used in
getting into the National Guard, which we've denied from the very
beginning,'' Quayle said.
   ``The facts are now out and there is no longer a discussion,''
he said.
   Records released Friday by the Indiana National Guard confirmed
both that the headquarters detachment he joined was under strength
when Quayle enlisted in May 1969 and that a slot also was available
at the time he transferred into the command's public information
unit.
</TEXT>
