<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Designers     08-27 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Designers,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Designers Organize to Battle AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California chef to the stars, clothing
designer Norma Kamali and Woody Allen's set designer are among the
celebrities who will show off their house-decorating skills in a $1
million AIDS fundraising effort.
   The group will redecorate an 18th century brownstone town house
off New York's Park Avenue, which then will be displayed to the
public in October.
   The artists want to raise the money for the Design Industries
Foundation for AIDS, which funds programs around the country. The
benefit's advisory board includes Barbara Walters, Walter Cronkite,
Yoko Ono, Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward.
   ``Just as design exploded with opportunity for talent ranging
from fashion to furniture, from cars to faucets, from cooktops to
cosmetics ... the design-related industries have been hit by a
plague more devastating than anyone could have imagined,'' the
foundation said in a statement.
   AIDS is ``wiping out the pool of design talent which has only
just blossomed in America. It's costing us our friends, our
colleagues, our heroes,'' the statement said.
   An anonymous couple donated their brownstone for the project and
will stay in their old apartment while the public troops through
the house.
   Chef Wolfgang Puck, the owner of the trendy West Hollywood
restaurant Spago, is creating the kitchen. Architect Michael Graves
is doing the foyer, while artist David Hockney chose the dining
room.
   Working on other rooms and the garden are Kamali; movie set
designer Santo Loquasto; architect Michael McDonough; American
interior designers Mario Buatta, Mark Hampton, John Saladino and
Jay Spectre, as well as France's Andree Putman and Italy's Ettore
Sottsass; and art dealer Holly Solomon.
   The $1 million fund-raising goal involves expected proceeds from
sales of donated objects and merchandise at the house, an art
auction and a $300-a-person dinner at which Robin Williams will
entertain and well-known chefs will prepare the food.
   Metropolitan Home will feature photographs of the show house in
a special February issue, donating 5 percent of the issue's
advertising revenues to the foundation, said Dorothy Kalins, the
magazine's editor and an organizer of the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
