<1ST_LINE>d i AM-Yugoslavia-Protest     08-27 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Protest,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Protest Treatment by Ethnic Albanians, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 10,000 chanting Serbs and
Montenegrins rallied Saturday to protest alleged harassment by
ethnic Albanians in the province of Kosovo, the official news
agency reported.
   The protest was held in Vrbas, about 110 miles north of Belgrade
in the Vojvodina province, the Tanjug news agency said.
   It said protesters shouted ``Give Us Arms'' and ``Better a Grave
than a Slave'' during the rally.
   The report said about 1,000 protesters had traveled from the
southern province of Kosovo for the rally in Vrbas. Serbs and
Montenegrins in Kosovo say they are being persecuted by ethnic
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population.
   The demonstration was the latest in a series called to support
demands by hardline communist leader Slobodan Milosejvic in the
nation's largest republic, Serbia.
   Though nominally autonomous, the provinces of Kosovo and
Vojvodina fall under partial administrative control of Serbia.
Milosejvic has demanded even stronger central control over the
provinces.
   Federal authorities, meanwhile, have warned against arousing
political passions and seeking solutions to problems on the streets.
   Government officials say more than 34,000 people have left
Kosovo, claiming discrimination and harassment, since riots broke
out in 1981 while ethnic Albanians demanded greater autonomy for
the province. At least nine people died in that unrest.
</TEXT>
