<HEAD>U.S. Soldier, 62 People Injured, During Melee By Rock Music Fans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHWEINFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier was seriously
injured and 62 others were hurt during overnight rioting by 2,500
rock music fans in Schweinfurt, police said Saturday.
   Police said groups of drunken fans went on a rampage through the
downtown area of the Bavarian city, attacking pedestrians and
smashing store and car windows, leaving the streets littered with
debris.
   In a statement to the news media, Schweinfurt police said
several hours of rampaging by the mostly youthful fans began
shortly before midnight Friday and continued until about 4 a.m.
   About 600 police were called in to quell the fans.
   Police said the American soldier, who was not identified by
name, was stabbed in the chest by an unknown assailant. The soldier
was taken to a local hospital where his condition was serious but
not life-threatening, police said.
   Those arrested face charges including vandalism, causing bodily
injury, and possession of illegal drugs, police said.
   Schweinfurt, with a population of about 52,000, is 135 miles
north of Munich.
   Some 40,000 rock music fans were expected in the city for a
Saturday afternoon open-air concert billed as ``Monsters of Rock,''
which includes such groups as Iron Maiden, David Lee Roth and Kiss.
   On Aug. 20, two young men were trampled to death and two
seriously injured when a large wall with a video screen collapsed
during a ``Monsters of Rock'' concert in Castle Donington, England.
