<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 2322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     08-27 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Protesters Freed In Atlanta, Arrested In Chicago</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-one anti-abortion activists arrested in Atlanta during
the Democratic National Convention revealed their identities to
police and were freed from jail Saturday, after spending 40 days
behind bars.
   Earlier Saturday, 14 people were arrested after they blocked the
entrance to an abortion clinic in Chicago, and in Pottstown, Pa.,
74 activists have been found guilty of trespassing stemming from a
July 5 demonstration outside a clinic.
   The protesters freed in Atlanta were among 134 arrested July 19.
Three of those arrested during the convention remained in jail,
including one who has been on a water-only fast since his arrest.
   ``I want everyone to know this is not a sign that we are giving
up,'' said the Rev. Edwin Arentsen, 71, of Illinois, who was
involved in the Atlanta demonstrations. ``We are going to return to
our homes and we are going to recruit more people to come to
Atlanta.
   ``This is not the end,'' he said. ``It's only the beginning.''
   The fasting inmate, who as part of his protest would identify
himself only as Baby John Doe, was hospitalized Friday, said Fulton
County sheriff's Maj. A.M. Alexander.
   ``His fast shows how determined and committed we are to stopping
abortions,'' said the Rev. Jessie Lee of New York, who left Atlanta
on an evening flight but vowed he would return.
   Officials with Operation Rescue, the New York-based group that
organized the protests, had said demonstrators hoped to overcrowd
the prison system by refusing to give their real names to police,
thus making them ineligible for bond.
   But job and family commitments have made staying in prison
difficult for protesters, who have come from New York, California,
Virginia and Illinois, said Operation Rescue spokeswoman Juli
Loesch.
   In Chicago, police were unable to take two of the protesters
into custody because they locked themselves to a bar attached to a
concrete block, and a locksmith failed to break them free after
working for more than an hour.
   The clinic's director called the protest by about 30
demonstrators an outrage, but an anti-abortion activist defended
the protesters' tactics.
   ``This is a death camp. As far as we're concerned this is just
exactly the same as Auschwitz or Buchenwald,'' Joseph Scheidler,
head of the Pro-Life Action League, said at an earlier protest at
another clinic.
   Seven men, six women and a 16-year-old girl were arrested for
sitting in front of the clinic door, said Patrolman Gene Nero. They
were to be charged with trespass, mob action, and resisting arrest,
police said.
   About 30 pro-choice activists gathered across the street and
cheered as the protesters were taken away.
   In Pennsylvania, 74 activists were found guilty Friday of
trespassing outside a women's health clinic in Paoli. Two more
hearings are scheduled to assess fines in the 591 arrests during a
demonstration organized by the Binghamton, N.Y.-based Operation
Rescue at the Women's Suburban Clinic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
