<HEAD>Ousted Panamanian President Visits Miami</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 2nd to UPDATE with Sosa quote. Adds
date of ouster in 4th graf pvs `Delvalle has...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle
slipped out of his hiding place in Panama City and arrived here
Saturday for what a spokesman called a brief and personal visit.
   Juan Sosa, the ambassador to the United States under Delvalle,
denied that Delvalle is fleeing Panama, WCIX-TV reported. Sosa
would not say whether the visit involves efforts to overthrow
Panama's military ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noreiga.
   ``He has an agenda,'' Sosa said. ``We're not divulging the
agenda for obvious reasons. President Delvalle is committed to
establishing a democracy in Panama _ that's as far as I will go in
my comment.''
   The U.S. government still recognizes Delvalle as his nation's
chief of state despite his February overthrow by Noriega.
   Delvalle has been in hiding in Panama with the help of the
United States since Feb. 26, when Noriega replaced him with Manuel
Solis Palma.
   An Air Force jet carrying Delvalle and his wife Marianella
arrived Saturday afternoon at the general aviation ramp at Miami
International Airport, WCIX reported. The couple were met by secret
service agents.
   The Delvalles had enough luggage to fill the bed of a pickup
truck. The secret service said Delvalle is under 24-hour protection
at an undisclosed South Florida location.
   Sosa, who is recognized as ambassador by the United States but
not by Noriega, said from Washington that he'll meet with Delvalle.
Sosa would not say whether Delvalle will meet with U.S.
administration officials.
   State Department officials were unavailable for comment Saturday
night.
   Delvalle visited Miami in July for a heart checkup. He had heart
bypass surgery about 10 years ago and is supposed to have a checkup
every six months, but this visit is unrelated to Delvalle's health,
Sosa said.
   After Noriega was indicted in Florida on charges of drug
trafficking, Delvalle tried to fire him as head of the country's
military. But Noriega refused to go, and instead had Delvalle
replaced.
</TEXT>
