<HEAD>School Boycott Enters Second Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attendance by black students in Amite
County schools rose slightly Friday, the second day of a boycott to
protest alleged racism in the school system.
   Officials said 486 students attended school Friday, 136 of them
black. On Thursday 460 students, including 126 blacks, attended the
first day of classes.
   Last year more than 2,100 students attended county schools.
Enrollment figures until the first day of school. The school system
is 76 percent black.
   About 25 pickets were outside the office of School
Superintendent Maurice Foreman. On Thursday, about 300 blacks,
about half of them children, rallied in front of the office.
   A list of demands was presented to the school board in July,
including: replacing Gloster High School's new principal, Robbie
Robertson, who is white, with a black person; hiring an assistant
superintendent of education, preferably black; and abandoning plans
to consolidate schools in Liberty and Gloster.
