<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-88 0758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv27-28-2Takes   08-27 0922</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 27-28-2 Takes,0954</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 27-28</NOTE>
<HEAD>NYSE's First Detailed Breakdown of Program Trading Raises New
Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simmering debate about program trading has
resurfaced with a New York Stock Exchange report that shows the
computer-driven technique accounted for only a tenth of the Big
Board's business last month.
   If the report was meant to show program trading isn't an
important element in the stock market's post-crash malaise, it
didn't convince many critics.
   Instead, the report raised new concern about what some opponents
of program trading see as the insidious influence of a high-tech
strategy that is little understood and widely feared by a broad
range of investors and brokers.
   ``I'm not in favor of program trading. The very philosophy is
alien to stock market investing,'' said Rao Chalasani, a market
strategist at the Cleveland-based investment firm of Prescott, Ball
& Turben Inc. ``Program trading has scared people away.''
   The NYSE, increasingly concerned about investor apathy since the
stock market collapse 10 months ago, issued its first monthly
report on program trading this past week.
   It showed that program trading comprised 10.1 percent of the
exchange's average daily volume of 166.9 million shares in July,
and that most program trading was conducted by a handful of big
investment firms.
   The nation's largest stock market, where the overwhelming level
of program trading is executed, said the report was part of what it
called a broader policy of making as much information available to
investors as possible.
   But the report got a lukewarm reaction at best, partly because
it gave no comparable figures for program trading during the crash
and its aftermath.
   Some studies have suggested the strategy accounted for 15
percent or more of the frenzied volume on Black Monday; others say
it was as low as 7 percent. But regardless of the volume level,
some critics say that's not the point and only obscures the real
concerns about program trading.
   ``Ten percent doesn't sound very high. But probably 90 to 95
percent of the time there are no programs being executed,'' said
Carmine Grigoli, equity portfolio strategist at the First Boston
Corp. in New York.
   ``It's just a very small timeframe that program trading tends to
move the market dramatically,'' Grigoli said. ``There you'll come
up with a very different picture.''
   Chalasani said, ``it's not the volume of program trading that
matters, but how concentrated it is and how fast it's executed.
That's what creates more volatility. Ten percent volume executed at
10 times during the day isn't the same as when it comes all in the
last ten minutes of the day.''
   John Bachmann, chairman of the Securities Industry Association,
was more receptive to the NYSE report, saying in a telephone
interview that it was at least a first step toward understanding
program trading's influence.
   ``The point is, we're doing something,'' he said. ``What's
significant is not the number. It's that you have a number. Whether
this is the number that's going to be the most illuminating, I have
my reservations.''
   Program trading was developed in the early stages of the 1982-87
bull market that collapsed with frightening speed last October.
   The strategy, which some studies have linked to the crash,
involves the use of high-speed computer delivery systems to quickly
buy and sell stocks or groups of stocks based on pre-programmed
mathematical formulas.
   The most common and controversial form of program trading is
called index arbitrage, in which traders buy stock-index futures in
Chicago futures markets and sell big groups of the underlying
stocks comprising those indexes in New York, or vice versa, to
profit from fleeting price disparities.
   Defenders of the practice claim it stabilizes stock prices by
keeping them from straying too far from futures prices. Critics
contend that because the high-risk futures markets are so volatile,
the linkage created by index arbitrage wrenches stock prices around
without regard to their real values.
   Moreover, the critics contend, the measly volumes of trading in
the post-crash market exaggerate the influence of this type of
trading and further discourage the genuine, long-term investing
central to the market's health.
   For example, some critics accuse program traders of manipulating
the market by pushing down index-futures prices to incite selloffs
in stock prices, then purchasing the stocks for less than they had
sold them earlier.
   Program traders also have been accused of a practice called
``front-running,'' in which they supposedly take profitable
positions in one market based on what they know will happen in
another market as a result of their computerized strategies.
   None of the questions about the effects of program trading were
settled by the statistics in the NYSE report, which provided no
analysis of their possible significance.
   Big Board spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin declined to comment on the
meaning or value of the numbers, saying they were meant to speak
for themselves. But she also said that in future monthly reports,
more statistics might be added.
   Since February, the exchange has enforced a temporary restraint
on program trading triggered when the Dow Jones industrial average
swings more than 50 points from the previous day's close, but the
effect of this so-called ``collar'' is debatable.
   Last month, the NYSE also proposed other restraints on program
trading in conjunction with the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, where
key stock-index futures contracts are traded. Those restraints,
which would replace the collar, include coordinated trading halts
if the Dow average drops 250 points in a day.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
