<1ST_LINE>a a BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv27-28   08-27 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 27-28,0792</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Weekend Editions Aug. 27-28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stock Volume Choked By Late Summer Rate Worries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After the October crash, did anyone seriously
expect Wall Streeters to do some frantic celebrating on the first
anniversary of the market's August 1987 peak?
   They did not. Investors marked the occasion by giving the market
the cold shoulder. Daily trading volume on the New York Stock
Exchange tumbled this past week to its lowest average for any week
in about 20 months.
   Traders and analysts who stayed around during the week to answer
the telephone blamed the slowdown on a combination of summer
doldrums, persistent worries about inflation and the economy, and
uncertainty about whether the Federal Reserve will push interest
rates higher.
   Rates available on fixed-income investments such as Treasury
issues are already offering wary investors a tempting return with
little risk.
   Yields on one-year Treasury bills, for instance, were more than
8.2 percent last week and five-year Treasury notes offered more
than 9 percent.
   On top of that, some market analysts say investors' skepticism
about stocks, sharpened by the frantic price collapse last October
that followed so closely after the market's August highs, remains
keen.
   They said the periodic and often unexpected bouts of
computer-driven program trading that still send the market through
some scary turns and the sour taste left by government
investigations of insider trading are also keeping the investors
out of the market.
   Investors got a reminder about program trading this past week
when the NYSE issued its first monthly measurement of the the
volume involved in the technique, saying it accounted for 10.1
percent of shares traded in July.
   ``You have an extremely high level of fear and apathy on the
part of investors generally,'' said Dean A. Gulis, director of
research for the brokerage firm Roney & Co. in Detroit. ``The
volume numbers are telling you more than anything you need to look
at.''
   Jack Garry, manager of institutional trading at Butcher & Singer
Inc. in Philadelphia, said, ``No one is really ready to make a
commitment to stocks.''
   ``We have some people nibbling at prices, sometimes adding to
existing positions, but there is just no real reason people can
find over the past few weeks to jump in and become buyers,'' he
said.
   That type of environment is especially troublesome in the late
summer when many traders and their clients are trying to take a
break from normal routines.
   In past years, traders often stayed on the job when the market
was busy. But Garry said this year's inactivity means ``nobody is
canceling their vacation plans. Not many people have reasons to
stick around.''
   The reduced interest in trading stocks ironically occurred on
the first anniversary of one of Wall Street's headiest days. The
Dow Jones industrial average reached its all-time peak of 2,722.42
on Aug. 25, 1987.
   This past week, the Dow Jones swung widely before finishing at
2,017.43, up 1.43 from its close a week ago.
   For the week, the NYSE composite index slipped 0.30 to 147.24;
the American Stock Exhange market-value index lost 1.16 to 293.87
and the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
2.99 to 374.43.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 117.29 million shares a day,
against 144.61 million shares the week before.
   That was the lowest for any week since volume averaged 114.25
million shares a day the week ended Jan. 2, 1987, which included
the New Years holiday.
   For some Wall Streeters, low volume could soon take on a
personal dimension. Traders are worried that if volume fails to
pick up after the Labor Day holiday, brokerage houses may lay off
employees.
   Perrin Long, who follows the brokerage business for Lipper
Analytical Securities Corp., said they may have genuine cause for
concern.
   ``I think there will be more layoffs, coming probably around the
15th of October,'' he said. ``Most firms will have good handle on
what third-quarter profits were by that time.''
   Long said brokerage executives ``can't put their fingers on what
has to happen to get individual and institutional investors more
interested.''
   Gene Jay Seagle, director of technical research for the
brokerage Gruntal Financial Inc. in New York, said he disagress
with market watchers who feel low volume is a sign stocks may be
headed lower.
   ``I think the selling has pretty much taken place,'' he said.
   But he attaches one cautionary note to his optimistic view _
that the Fed refrains from giving ``another jerk on the reins'' by
tightening credit.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug 27-28</NOTE>
