<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 27-28</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds weekly price trends</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: ... near future.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Wheat for September delivery settled Friday at $3.90 a bushel
compared with $3.91} a week earlier; September corn dropped to
$2.77\ a bushel from $2.87\; September oats fell to $2.54 a bushel
from $2.59; and September soybeans slid to $8.31{ a bushel from
$8.71.
   Cattle futures advanced while pork futures were mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   October live cattle rose to 72.97 cents a pound from 71.87
cents; September feeder cattle moved to 82.25 cents a pound from
81.47 cents; October hogs fell to 41.05 cents a pound from 41.45
cents; and February frozen pork bellies climbed to 54.82 cents a
pound from 54.17 cents.
   Precious metals futures were nearly unchanged on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   October gold was unchanged at $435.60 a troy ounce; September
silver fell 1 cent to $6.66 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   October West Texas Intermediate crude oil dipped to $15.34 a
barrel from $15.85; September heating oil dropped to 42.67 cents a
gallon from 44.48 cents; and September unleaded gasoline fell to
46.79 cents a gallon from 47.59.
</TEXT>
