<HEAD>Oil Prices Recover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have bounced back from a
steep slide but the market's underlying sentiment remains bearish.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, edged up 3 cents a barrel Friday to close at $15.34.
Most other contract months were unchanged.
   The October crude contract fell 37 cents a barrel in Thursday's
trading.
   Prices of refined oil products traded on the exchange also rose.
Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline
rose 0.35 cent to finish at 46.79 cents a gallon. Wholesale heating
oil for September advanced 0.22 cent to 42.67 cents a gallon.
   On Thursday, oil futures tumbled sharply on reports that oil
production by the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries had surged anew.
   The oil futures market has been inactive in recent weeks without
news on supply and demand to guide it. Analysts said Thursday's
reports on OPEC provided the first sign of direction in some time,
with prices likely to weaken further as the increased oil outflow
reaches consuming nations.
   Friday's recovery did not signal a change in market sentiment,
analysts said, but was mainly due to buying late in the session by
traders who wanted to balance their positions before the weekend.
   ``The market is continuing in a bearish trend,'' said Chris
Gohler, an oil futures broker with Elders Futures Inc. ``The market
just has a tendency to spike back very quickly.''
   He also noted gasoline prices are being supported by fairly
tight supplies in the physical market and by some oil refineries
already converting their facilities to prepare for increased
heating oil production for the winter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
