<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     08-27 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Income Up, Spending Slows, Markets Sleep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Government economic figures suggested the inflationary threat
isn't as acute as some people fear, but the news wasn't enough to
wake Wall Street, which slumbered through the slowest trading day
of the year.
   The Commerce Department said Friday that Americans' personal
incomes, bolstered by the biggest increase in wages in seven
months, rose 0.6 percent in July while consumer spending slowed
because of a drop in auto sales.
   The increase in incomes was identical to the June advance. But
spending on personal consumption, which includes everything except
interest payments on debt, rose a 0.5 percent in July, less than
half the 1.1 percent June advance.
   As with other recent statistics, economists found signs of
growing inflationary pressures in the report, primarily in a 1
percent gain in wages and salaries, the biggest rise in this key
component since last December.
   But others said the slowdown in spending was an
anti-inflationary sign, because it suggested demand for goods
wasn't overwhelming the ability of factories and stores to supply
them.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, in Los Angeles with
President Reagan, called the report ``good news.''
   ``The figures in the report are favorable, with steady income
growth, good growth in consumer spending and an in the personal
saving rate,'' Fitzwater said.
   But there was little reaction on Wall Street, where stocks
gained slightly and volume on the New York Stock Exchange slumped
to 89.24 million shares, the lowest level since an 86.36 million
share day last Nov. 27, the Friday after Thanksgiving. Bond prices
also ended little changed in slack trading.
   ``I just think a lot of people are finding an excuse to take
vacations or an early Labor Day,'' said Lawrence R. Helfand,
manager of retail sales at the Chicago-based investment firm Rodman
& Renshaw Inc. ``There's no question that people are just sitting
on the sidelines.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
